18	A new decade	After a few days of festive gorging around Guadalajara and enjoying a hotel room with hot water on demand and a lack of uninvited insect guests I rode south out of Guadalajara towards Lago Chapala. The first 20km or so of riding out of a big city were always going to be pretty unpleasant as I dealt with the crazy bus drivers and big dirty trucks spewing fumes everywhere. My cyclist sixth sense was in overdrive with the standard of driving on display. One of my favourite driving practices Ive noticed in Mexico is one use for indicators. Say a taxi is driving along slowly next to the pavement. The driver starts indicating left (they drive on the right in Mexico). This can either mean Im about to pull in and stop, please overtake me or Im about to pull out into the traffic, dont overtake me. Two completely contradicting actions with absolutely no way to tell which the driver is actually going to carry out.\n\nI reached the town of Chapala in one piece and found somewhere to have some lunch where I had a nice chat with the lady running the taco stand. It was here where I first noticed what I think is evidence of my Spanish improving - immediate and crushing internal cringing when I make a silly mistake. Whereas in the past I might have unknowingly made a silly mistake, the patient Mexican on the other side of the conversation would have just let it slide because they knew what I meant to say. Now however, I tend to notice my mistakes almost immediately and feel like a right plonker. In this instance I asked for otro juego de naranja por favor. Unfortunately this translates as another orange game please which is obviously gibberish. The word I wanted to use was the very similar sounding jugo meaning juice. Whoops. One positive is that once you make a particular mistake once, youre unlikely to repeat it as the embarrassment really lodges it into your mind.\n\nAfter Chapala the riding improved hugely as I followed a quiet rural road along the coast of Lago Chapala to the town of Mezcala. In an effort to save some money I asked the guy running the small police station in the town hall if I could kip in a corner somewhere for the night. He said that normally he would say yes but there was some sort of celebration on in town tonight so he was expecting to be busy rounding up unruly drunks all night. Fair enough I thought, and nipped round the corner to the only hotel in town. Dinner in Mezcala was gigante sorta especial which means enormous special sandwich. Being a hungry cyclist I cockily ordered two of them but knew I was in trouble straight away as the waitress raised her eyebrows at me in an extremely sceptical manner. Sure enough, two very tasty but gargantuan sandwiches soon arrived. I struggled my way through as a matter of pride and retired to my hotel room to softly groan in agony.\n\nFrom Mezcala I climbed up from the lake with a steep cobbled road making for slow and bumpy progress. From the top of the climb I descended to Poneitlan where I joined the bigger roads once more. The spacing of the towns meant I had my longest day of the trip so far at 132km. I arrived in Churintzio tired, hungry and looking forward to a good nights rest. Unfortunately the hotel was hosting a 90th birthday party with what must be the loudest brass band in Mexico giving it everything they had. I had hoped that, with it being a 90th birthday party, they might pack it in at a sensible hour. Alas, it was not to be. Once again, the earplugs that Ive kept from the flight to Seattle proved invaluable.\n\nI rode from Mezcala to the large town of Morelia along smaller back roads where possible, enjoying the sights and atmosphere away from the larger roads. Highlights included having to apologetically push my bike through a huge wedding crowd blocking the road through a tiny village and being able to enjoy the surroundings without the constant armco barrier to my side. I took a day off in Morelia over New Year. I cant offer any insights into Mexican traditions on New Years Eve as I was in bed and asleep by 9.30pm after feeling pretty lethargic and ropey with a sore throat all day. The rock n roll life of a cycle tourist!\n\nThe road out of Morelia made for a great days riding as I climbed up to almost 3000m through Mil Cumbres (Thousand Peaks) before a long, flowing descent to Ciudad Hidalgo. Great views all day long with the pine forests above about 2300m almost making me feel like I was back in Washington again!\n\nThe ride the next day wasnt as good as there was much more noisy impatient traffic and a blustery wind blowing dust into my eyes all day. It also wasnt a particularly nice area, as I cycled past plenty of the ubiquitous smouldering Latin American landfills and a dead dog that had obviously been shot. I had hoped to ride a bit further but when I got to the town of Zitcuaro I was pretty fed up and not enjoying myself so I decided to call it a day and carry on the following morning. The day did finish on a high note though with the following amusing interaction over dinner.\n\nI was just finishing up my daily dose of tacos (chorizo and frijoles in case you were interested) and asked the guy sitting next to me (Adolpho) if he could pass me a napkin so I could deal with the mess that inevitably occurs whilst eating meat, salsa and guacamole barely contained in a small tortilla. I wasnt sure of the word for napkin in Spanish so I asked him after he had passed me one. I make a habit of doing this because a) it expands my vocabulary and b) is almost always followed by me being asked where Im from, giving me the perfect opportunity to explain that I am not American, which is almost always the assumption. This time, I got my favourite reaction so to me saying Im a Brit:\n\n**Toby**: Disculpame seor, puede pasarme uno de esos? [Excuse me, can you pass me one of those?]\n**Adolpho**: Por suspuesto, aqu tienes [Of course, here you are]\n**Toby**: Y come se llama estos en estaol? [And what do you call these in Spanish?]\n**Adolpho**: Servilletas. Donde vienes? Americano, verdad? [Serviettes. Where are you from? American, right?]\n**Toby**: No no, soy de Reino Unido, Escocia de hecho [No no, Im from the UK, Scotland in fact]\n**Adolpho**: Ayyyy muy bien, ms fina, mucha ms fina [Ooohhhh very good! More refined, much more refined]\n\nAdolpho then proceeded to offer me multiple blessings for health, acquisition of material goods and my spirit for the coming year before offering to pay for my dinner. Unfortunately the sincerity of all these compliments and kind words were slightly undermined by his parting words:\n\n**Adolpho**: Acabo de tomar cinco cervezas [Ive just had five beers] (accompanied by the internationally recognised miming for Im slightly pissed")	Seeing in 2020 with cobbled climbs, Mexican brass bands and drunken compliments	mexico	a-new-decade	2023-02-19 20:07:42.191	2023-02-19 20:15:01.565	2023-02-19 20:15:01.547	1	1	2020-01-02
19	Mexico City	From Zitacuaro I climbed up to Macho de Agua along a twisting road (and ill advised dirt road shortcut) with views back over the way Id come. Im glad Id decided to call it a day in Zitacuaro the day before as if Id carried on I would have just stormed my way up the climb with my head down and not enjoyed the scenery or the climb. From the top of the climb the road followed a series of undulations towards Toluca. I stopped for a late lunch of quesadillas (basically a tortilla filled with melted cheese and normally some sort of meat). The filling in this case appeared to basically be a pork chop, with the bone still in, which meant I had to dismantle the quesadilla and pick all the meat off the bone before reassembling my lunch. Seems to defeat the point of an easily handled all in one lunch package really!\n\nI arrived in Toluca and found the apartment of Seth, who makes bicycle bags for a living and had kindly agreed to host me for a couple of days. The first surprise came after Id showered and changed and Seth asked if I was hungry. I said yes, expecting to be taken to some delicious local taco stand. Ten minutes later I was following Seth as he wove through the Toluca traffic, destination still unknown to me. After a white knuckle ride - Seth has a very different traffic risk tolerance to me leading to some moments where I hoped Adolpho had remembered to give me a blessing offering protection from Mexican drivers - we arrived at a big event hall with a party in full swing. Apparently I had managed to swing an invite to Seths cousins 40th birthday! After a round of introductions where people mostly gave me funny looks, no doubt wondering what this skinny sunburnt gringo was doing at their party, we helped ourself to the (excellent) tacos and a couple of beers. Shortly afterwards the music started and, knowing full well what was coming, I started making it very clear in my best Spanish that I did not enjoy dancing. Unfortunately my faltering protestations were no match for the collective will of a gaggle of middle aged Mexican women and I was soon exhibiting my terrible moves with a series of aunts.\n\nId decided to take a side trip into Mexico City to have a look around and catch up with Ren (who you may remember from Baja and the ferry to Mazatln) again while he was there waiting for his flight to Cuba. The next morning I hopped on the bus and after some lunch, checked into the same hostel as Ren. It felt quite strange being in a busy big city again with lots of the multinational shops and brands from home being represented. That afternoon, we went to the National Anthropology Museum which charts the history of Mexican culture from prehistoric times to the modern day. Its a huge museum, with a separate area for each geographical area of Mexico. There is easily enough material there for a couple of days browsing but being hungry cyclists, after a few hours of looking at sculptures and pots, our thoughts soon turned to a late afternoon snack. We grabbed a sandwich from a stall outside the museum and watch a bizarre spectacle where four men in traditional clothing hung upside down from a tall pole and descended whilst spinning round and playing instruments. Subsequent research reveals it was the Danza de los Voladores so Im sure you can search for it on Youtube or something for a better explanation than Ive just given. In the evening we walked around the historical centre of Mexico City which is has some very grand old buildings and almost feels like the centre of Madrid than somewhere in Mexico. Another surprising aspect was the sheer number of people walking around. Id expected it to be busy but was taken aback a bit - the cars are forced to remain stationary as the streets are completely full with a sea of pedestrians.\n\nI left Toluca a couple of days later in the direction of a couple of national parks with big climbs promising good views. On the way there I rode through a nature reserve which came complete with a stinking river full of rubbish. I overnighted in Xalatlaco before climbing up into the Parque Nacional Cumbres del Ajusco. The steep ramps out of town had me out of breath but thankfully the gradients soon eased to something more manageable as the corn fields gave way to pine forests. The smog layer over Mexico City was pretty startling, to me it definitely looked worse than the smoke plume Id seen from the wildfire in California. I crested the climb at 3,600m and started the descent which was fast but littered with lethal potholes and unmarked speed bumps hidden in the dappled shade. I had a close call coming into a small town when one of the stealth speed bumps suddenly appeared. I slammed on my brakes but a little too late as I was flung off my seat and thankfully came down astride the top tube rather than being thrown off the bike. I skidded to a halt with the rear wheel locked up and my feet scraping along the ground to the great amusement of some onlookers.\n\nFrom here I had to ride across the very outskirts of the Mexico City urban sprawl which was thoroughly unpleasant. I hit it at the mid afternoon rush hour so the traffic was basically at gridlock with the fleets of wretched old minibuses spewing out horrible fumes. Once I was out of the worst of the traffic, Google Maps decide to take me down some stupid roads which mainly consisted of horrible dusty sand. I arrived in Amecameca caked in dust and continuously coughing from the fumes. Of course I was aware that urban air pollution was a problem before now but Id never experienced it so clearly. It must be absolutely horrible for the people that live there permanently. From Amecameca there were clear views of Popocatpetl, an active volcano. So active in fact that I watched it puff out smoke and ash from the town square as I ate my ice cream.\n\nI got up early the next day to start my climb up to Paso de Cortes, a saddle between Popocatpetl and another volcano next to it. The climb definitely seemed tougher than the one the day before, whether that was because it was actually harder or just because I had some residual fatigue in my legs I dont know. On the way up I overtook lots of people on unloaded bikes which is always satisfying. I did my best to give a cheery buenos dis as I passed them, making the climb look effortless before gasping for air once safely out of earshot. After a few hours I arrived at the top and suddenly became a minor celebrity as all the riders Id overtaken arrived and expressed their disbelief at how rapido I was. After being asked to pose for a round of photos with them I started my downhill ride down the other side. At the time, I was slightly annoyed that the volcano didnt have the decency to do anything exciting for my photos while I was at the top but it has since transpired that a few hours after I rode past, it became slightly more active than I would be comfortable with (see postscript). Maybe geology isnt as dull as my Dad manages to make it sound after all! I was glad to be getting off the top as this time Id noticed the altitude manifesting itself as a slight headache and lack of appetite at the top. I descended on a bumpy dirt track with the volcano peeking through the gaps in the trees. I hot the tarmac and had a nice easy downhill slide in the sun to the picturesque town of Atlixco. From here I have a three or four day run into Oaxaca where Ive been reassured the food is particularly excellent!\n\nP.S. I just googled the Popocatpetl to get the correct spelling and it turns out it erupted a few hours after I cycled past it! Video here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gHdFN1BYnbs\n	Dancing with Mexican aunts and a close call with a volcano	mexico	mexico-city	2023-02-19 20:37:25.399	2023-02-19 20:37:27.373	2023-02-19 20:37:27.369	1	1	2020-01-10
2	Seattle	Greetings from Seattle! Ive been here for a couple of days now, doing a bit of sightseeing and general admin before starting the bike ride proper on Saturday.\n\nHowever, before you get to hear about Seattle Im afraid you have to get through a little bit of gloating about my over the top first class flight experience. When I booked my flight out for this trip, I decided to cash in a whole bunch of air miles and book myself into first class. Because what better way is there to begin a year slumming it in a tent than by reminding yourself of all the luxuries youll be going without? I arrived at Heathrow about five hours before my flight which is complete overkill but a) I wanted plenty of time to treat myself in the lounge before taking off and b) it was that or hang around in my budget hotel room. I manoeuvred my unwieldy bike box into the dedicated first class check in wing without bumping into any of the expensive looking fittings and got to a desk straight away. Now normally when travelling with a bike box, the check in process is fraught with anxiety as you try and charm your way into convincing the check in agent not to charge you an excess baggage fee before you are made to drag your bike box to the overside baggage belt which is, without fail, on the opposite side of the terminal. There was none of that this time. No probing questions asked about the weight of my massive cardboard box and shortly afterwards a man was summoned on the walkie talkie to take my bike to oversized baggage for me, leaving me free to swan through security to the Concorde Room lounge (what British Airways call their first class lounge) where I swiftly ordered some brunch. I think the time from arriving at check in to having eggs benedict put in front of me was less than ten minutes.\n\nThere followed a few hours of lounging on a day bed whilst being fed a seemingly endless supply of truffled nuts and champagne before it was time to head to the gate. The decadence continued during the flight as I wined and dined my way across the Atlantic (see photos) before arriving into Seattle early in the evening where I checked into an airport hotel to avoid having to faff around getting myself and a bike into the centre of Seattle whilst tired from the journey.\n\nThe next day I assembled my bike at the airport, which has a fully kitted out bike workshop area with tools, pump and work stand! The excellent cycling infrastructure continued when I rode from the airport to my hostel in downtown Seattle - I think about 90-95% of the ride was on dedicated bike paths or a segregated lane on the road. Bristol City Council, take note!\n\nThe following day or so was spent wandering around Seattle having a bit of an explore and running a few errands. I had hoped to see a bit more and take a few more photos but an unfortunate freak bout of food poisoning or something (on day two of the trip, come on!), combined with the jet lag means that Ive been feeling pretty knackered. Despite that, I had a walk along the seafront and a look around Pike Place Market. The fish at the market were particularly impressive, absolutely massive compared to the tiddlers we get back in the UK. One of the fish stalls moves their fish around not by passing it from one person to other like any sensible would do, but by throwing it from one side of the stall to the other. To me, the risk-reward benefits dont seem to be worth it - I wonder how often an unsuspecting passer by is blindsided by a massive airborne Alaskan salmon?!\n\nI also had a look around the REI flagship store which is heaven to someone with a mild outdoor gear acquisition addiction. Three massive floors of all the ultralight, overpriced gadgets I never knew I needed. Its lucky that I have limited carrying capacity on the bike or that could have ended up being a financially crippling shopping trip. Soon after, I encountered my first example of obscene American portion sizes. I was at one of these places where you sit at the bar and order pizza by the slice and thought that two slices would be enough - I wasn't that hungry and they were loaded with toppings. When they arrived, each slice alone was getting on for the size of a whole pizza in the UK! Needless to say, I admitted defeat and one slice went into a takeaway box.\n\nTomorrow I hope to burn off some of my pizza based excess with the start the bike ride proper with a winding route on bike paths through the suburbs of Seattle before picking up the John Wayne Pioneer Trail through Iron Horse State Park and past Rattlesnake Lake (I have to admit, the place names are cooler here). From there I hope to follow US Forestry Service dirt roads south before dropping down into Rainer National Park and hopefully getting my first view of Mount Rainer itself. Then it's due south along the back roads, past Mount St. Helens and into Portland from where you can expect the next update in four or five days time!	How the other half fly	usa	seattle	2023-02-17 09:22:03.664	2023-02-17 11:38:59.296	2023-02-17 09:22:39.557	1	1	2019-10-04
32	Coffee Country	I had planned my departure from Medelln to be on a Sunday to take advantage of the ciclovia when heading out of town. All the big cities in Colombia have a ciclovia on Sunday mornings where large tracts of roads are closed to vehicular traffic to allow people to cycle, run, walk, rollerblade etc without having to worry about traffic. The first ciclovia was set up in Bogota in the 70s and the concept has since spread to the other large cities in Colombia, Medelln included. \n\nI made my way out of town along the main road, weaving my way through the walkers and runners (but Id take weaving through walkers over dealing with three lanes of heavy traffic any day!). There was a great atmosphere with pumping music, stalls selling snacks and drinks and local bike shops with bike maintenance workshops lining the route. When I reached the southern outskirts of the city around Sabaneta the ciclovia ended and I was back on the open roads. There was a reasonable amount of traffic but a massive shoulder for me to ride on and loads of other cyclists out on their weekend rides from the city. I followed the rolling main road for a bit before turning off and taking a smaller back road through the outskirts of Amag before heading south for my planned overnight stop of Fredonia. I had a bite to eat for lunch near Amag before the descent then climb up to Fredonia. I really struggled on the climb up to Fredonia, probably due to a combination of the heat, the steepness of the climb and not being used to riding a loaded touring bike. I found it so hard that I actually ended up calling it a day only about 4km short of Fredonia at a lovely hotel/ranch called Hotel Los Robles. This actually turned out to be a pretty good move as for twenty quid I had the run of the place and its gardens to myself and dinner, breakfast and lunch the next day all included! I decided just to chill out at Los Robles the following morning and then pootle up the remaining 4km to Fredonia early the following afternoon and stay there as originally planned. Not quite the start I had imagined but no point ruining myself in the first few days!\n\nFrom Fredonia I had a slightly longer day which started with a nice descent down to Puente Iglesias on the Rio Cauca. Being down at the bottom of the valley it was absolutely stinking hot again. I then had to knock out about 18km along the main road to La Pintada where I stopped for a quick bite to eat. I wasnt a massive fan of La Pintada, it was basically a hot, noisy strip of crappy restaurants which seemed to basically just be a giant truck stop. After La Pintada the riding improved a lot as I took a dirt back road which initially rolled along next to the Rio Aures before another tough, steep climb up to the village of Arma. I had an additional bit of time pressure this time as for the last half hour or so I could hear the afternoon thunderstorm gradually catching up with me. I arrived in Arma just in time as no sooner had I ordered coffee, chocolate brownie and ice cream the heavens opened with full on thunder and lightning. I was a little bit worried as I hadnt noticed anywhere to stay on the way into town but after asking one of the waitresses it turned out there was a guesthouse just around the corner so I dashed around there and checked into my 5 room and dried off. \n\nAfter Arma the towns are placed such that I could either do about 35km days or about 60-70km days. With how tough the first couple of days had been I opted for the 35km option. This is quite a bit shorter than I would normally like to do in a day but with the amount of climbing involved and it being the first week I thought it sensible to take it easy. Lunch the next day (after some more climbing) was the town of Aguadas. While sitting in the square scouting out somewhere to eat I got talking to a Colombian cyclist who assured me that the climbs to come on my route were less steep than the ones Id encountered so far. This was good news as there is nothing worse than a climb being too steep for you to comfortably spin away in your bottom gear so you have to really grind away at it. Just as I pulled up outside my chosen restaurant, an old guy running a motorcycle garage next door offered to look after my bike inside his garage rather than me having to leave it on the street. After lunch we chatted a bit and he explained the concept of el putas de Aguadas. Apparently this is quite a common saying across Colombia and it basically means someone who can do anything and fears nothing. I think it comes from the famously hardy farm workers who used to work across the region a couple of hundred years ago. As I left he told me that I was los putas de Aguadas which I took as quite the compliment! After an afternoon of rolling downhill, I finished up for the day in the town of Pcora. \n\nThe next day started with a climb straight out of town (are you sensing a theme here) before descending down into the valley again. The sense of power in the water flowing through the river at the bottom was quite something, it was really rolling and boiling away with boulders being clunked into each other. Not surprising really when you think about how much it rains here and how much water must run off these steep sided hills. As promised by the cyclist in Aguadas, the climb up to Salamina was less steep and I was able to take my time heading up it and enjoy the experience. Another cyclist on a very fancy road bike passed me twice as he did hill reps with encouraging shouts of venga venga venga and high fives both times. Salamina was a really nice town with lots of original buildings painted all sorts of bright colours. After a bit of research it turns out it is one of Colombias heritage towns. The hotel I was staying in was an old converted school. This became pertinent when, whilst walking around the square later that afternoon, an older guy in poncho and sombrero sitting outside a bar shouted over to me and asked if I wanted to sit down for a chat. He said he always asks people who are obviously solo travellers if they want a chat so they dont feel lonely which is a nice thing to do! Turns out before he retired he used to teach at the very school/hotel I was staying at! He bought me a couple of beers and we chatted about my trip, foods I should try in Colombia and his grandchildren in Houston. Hes flying over to visit them there for the first time in a few weeks but is terrified of flying. I tried to assure him that as an aerospace engineer I was well qualified to tell him flying to Houston was orders of magnitude safer than the terrifying mountain road bus journeys he takes every day but Im not sure he believed me. \n\nNext stop was Neira - this would be a slightly longer ride with a bit more climbing but given the easier grades on the climbs and my improving fitness I was feeling up to it. I bounced my way up and down (there dont seem to be any flat roads here at all) and soon was on the final climb up to Neira. This seemed to drag on for longer than Id expected but that was probably down to faltering energy levels at the end of the day. As I entered the outskirts of Neira I overheard one young guy at the side of the road say to his friend what the hell is this crazy gringo doing. I managed to get out a swift the crazy gringo isnt sure either which got some laughs - I dont think they were expecting me to have understood their Spanish! Finding my way into Neira itself from the main road was slightly tricky as there was no obvious way in. I ended up taking an INCREDIBLY steep little side street. All the towns here seem to be built on the top of ridges so the main drag is often flat but the side streets off of it are often unfeasibly steep. This particular street in Neira was so steep I struggled to even push my bike up it on foot. I wasnt such a fan of Neira as it didnt seem to have the charm of previous towns like Salamina with their period buildings and so on.\n\nFrom Neira it was another shortish ride to the larger town (almost city I guess) of Manizales where Id planned to take a day or two off. The first section of this ride was pleasant enough but it got a bit grotty upon reaching the outskirts of Manizales with all the roadside light industry and traffic fumes (which are never fun when youre breathing heavily on a climb). There was one point where there was a one way system in place due to some roadworks with workers with the stop/go signs. We were stopped for about five minutes by which time quite the crowd of motorbikes had gathered and were revving their engines impatiently. I swear the woman with the sign gave us a 3-2-1 before turning the sign to go and all hell broke loose. The section of road we were all heading for was significantly narrower than the bit of road wed all been waiting on so it was a mad rush to get there first. Somehow we all managed to funnel into the narrow roadworks without incident - it reminded me a bit of the start of a cyclocross race where everyone is rushing to get into the first bit of narrow technical riding at the front of the pack.\n\nIm currently enjoying a couple of days off in Manizales to sightsee and chill out before continuing on. Manizales is pretty nice with a fair bit to do. It has the cathedral with the tallest spire in Colombia which you can pay a couple of quid to go up which I did. Climbing up through the inside of the gradually narrowing spire and the views at the top were both pretty cool. Couple of interesting facts about the cathedral: it appears to be made entirely of reinforced concrete (which actually kind of works) and the Italian designer was scared of heights so during construction he supervised the work by telescope from ground level rather than going up the scaffolding himself! I also took a walk up to the neighbourhood of Chispe which provides some nice views over the lower reaches of Manizales and out to the surrounding hills.\n\nFrom here Ill spend a couple of days climbing up to and riding along the flanks of a volcano in the Nevado del Ruiz national park just to the south of Manizales. This will see me getting up to 4,000m and doing my first spot of camping so things should hopefully get a bit more adventurous!  From there Ill have a big descent down into the next big valley which Ill be following south for a while as I head down towards Ecuador. 	It's all so green!	colombia	coffee-country	2023-03-20 01:34:24.121	2023-03-20 01:53:12.381	2023-03-20 01:50:30.643	1	1	2023-03-19
20	Struggling into Oaxaca	I woke up in Atlixco the next morning with sore legs and a strong desire to remain wrapped up in my duvet rather than get on the bike. Not unusual after a few days of big climbs so I paid up for another night in the hotel and went out to explore Atlixco properly. It had seemed like a nice place the previous evening so I was glad for a chance to spend a bit more time there. I went to grab a late breakfast at the market. I love these slightly chaotic places, the sweet smell of dried chillis, the noise of every stall owner shouting out their menu and the sight of a strange new fruit or vegetable almost every time. I found a spot at a stall and ordered some huevos a la mexicana (basically scrambled eggs with onion, tomato and chilli). The woman behind the counter asked if I wanted some tortillas to go with it and after I had replied in the affirmative, she turned her face to the roof, took a deep breath and screamed TORTIIIIIIILAS at seemingly no-one in particular like some sort of Mexican distress signal. In the blink of an eye, a young girl was heeding the call, practically sprinting through the market with a stack of tortillas under one arm whilst she used the other to elbow unsuspecting punters out of the way.\n\nThe next day should have been an easy one in theory, with a nice downhill slide out of Atlixco before a couple of small hills at the end of the day. In reality, I was feeling pretty knackered even on the downhill and the legs felt completely empty on the uphill segments. After going over what I had eaten the previous day, I put it down to possible insufficient rest day fuelling and/or not eating enough salts in the hot weather. I tried to make up for this by having a pre-dinner snack of a crisp sandwich followed by a mountain of spaghetti followed by an early night.\n\nThe next day started off alright with a nice early start in the cool morning air. The road gradually climbed up through scenery that reminded me of the desert sections in the interior of Baja California. After a descent to Acatln de Osorio, where I had a little break, the road started rising again in short climb/descent bursts. I dont particularly like this sort of terrain as I find it hard to get into a nice rhythm and soon I felt like I was flagging. I stopped for a few quesadillas and a sugary drink in an effort to revive my legs but it exactly the opposite effect. The final climb up to the Oaxaca state border was a real struggle as I had to stop for constant breaks and, despite knowing I needed to keep eating and drinking to avoid grinding to a halt, didnt find any of my food that appetising and could only handle sips of water. I couldnt understand why I was finding it so difficult having ticked all the boxes of eating loads of carbs, drinking plenty of water and resting well. In the first signs that maybe the root of the problem was in my head, I started getting inexplicably irritated at tiny things like a encouraging toot from a passing motorcycle, a slightly rough section of tarmac or a tiny rise in the middle of the descent to Huajuapan. That evening I repeated the carbs-salt-water-sleep cycle which in theory should fix most endurance exercise woes.\n\nThe aim for the next day was Asuncin Nochixtln, about 90km away. I got on the bike and set off with a heavy sigh, which is not normally a good sign! I knew almost straight away that I wasnt going to make it to Nochixtln with a strong wind blowing in my face as I moodily plugged my up the climbs, not even bothering to look around at the (actually quite nice) scenery. I tried all the tricks in the book to try and lift my spirits, breaking out the emergency chocolate and putting on my designated cheer-up album (Screamadelica by Primal Scream for those interested). Despite this, I noticed myself subconsciously checking over my shoulder for likely looking pickups to thumb a lift from. Some cyclist pride took over and I made it over the climbs to the town of Tamazaulapan. Id only managed about 40km but realistically I knew I wasnt going any further that day - the question was whether to sleep on it and continue to Nochixtln the next day or just cut my losses and hop onto a bus to Oaxaca there and then. I sat on a bench sweating in the midday sun whilst in my mind a cyclists innate stubbornness against hitching a ride battled against the knowledge that two previous evenings of early nights and heavy carbs hadnt improved matters, so why would another be any different? In the end, my Mum told me I was being an idiot and to just get on the bloody bus, which is what I ended up doing.\n\nThinking things over on the ride to Oaxaca, I realised that for some reason Id lost a good chunk of my enthusiasm for the riding side of things since leaving Mexico City and that my struggles over the past few days probably hadnt been due to eating insufficient cheap Mexican cookies but more just down to being a bit fed up. Ive been on the road for just over three months and couldnt remember the last time Id been in one place for more than 96 hours. I decided to spend at least a week in Oaxaca, reasoning that having a holiday from the holiday might help reset things a bit. I booked an AirBnB so I would have my own base and somewhere I could indulge in some home comforts like cooking something more elaborate than pasta and sauce.\n\nThe past week or so has been spent exploring Oaxaca and its many interesting side streets, taking a side trip to the ruins at Monte Alban and indulging in a couple of proper coffee shops. The food has been great in Oaxaca as well with a wide variety on offer, from various types of mole to fried grasshoppers and my new favourite Mexican street food, tlayudas. A tlayuda is basically a giant tortilla which is spread with pork fat, beans, stringy Oaxaca cheese and loads of veg before being folded in half and toasted over coals until the tortilla is crispy and the cheese is all melted. Lovely. I enjoyed the ruins at Monte Alban much more than those near Mexico City. Although they were smaller in scale, they were vastly less busy, meaning it was quite pleasant to wander around and explore without having to wait in endless queues.\n\nI have a couple more days of calorie replacement therapy in Oaxaca before continuing south towards San Cristobal de las Casas and then onto the border with Guatemala where I look forward to having to learn a whole new set of Spanish words and turns of phrase, having just got used to the Mexican ones!	When mainlining carbs doesn't seem to work	mexico	struggling-into-oaxaca	2023-02-19 20:53:04.566	2023-02-19 21:02:29.831	2023-02-19 21:02:29.827	1	1	2020-01-19
3	If you go down to the woods today...	On Saturday morning I packed up my bike bags and checked out of my hostel like I have done dozens of times on cycle tours before, however this time was a little bit more special. My journey across two continents, more than a dozen countries and who knows how many pedal strokes began in a neglected alley behind a hostel in Seattle with a homeless man looking through the bins for any dregs in the discarded booze bottles. Not the most auspicious of locations, but every journey has to start somewhere!\n\nSaturday morning was mainly made up of the frustrating stop-start riding that always comes with leaving a big city. All the stopping for traffic lights, to check the map or to correct a wrong turn all adds up to pretty slow progress. I managed to find my way onto the Mountain to Sound Greenway which is a pretty nice shared use path which roughly follows the I90 corridor. I had a couple of people notice the bike and ask where I was headed, people seem a lot more open to approaching strangers to chat than us reserved Brits. One of them, a motorcyclist called Dave (theres always a Dave isnt there?), pulled over and flagged me down. Turns out he does a lot of riding himself and wanted to ask if I needed any spares or food as his house was just round the corner. He said hell be riding through Baja in Mexico in December so our paths may cross again!\n\nSoon I was riding through Snoqualmie and North Bend and onto the John Wayne Pioneer Trail. This is a trail which I think goes all the way east to Idaho and follows the course of an old 1800s railway line so it has loads of those cool old railway bridges of the style you see in Westerns. It must have been tricky to build as it seemed to be clinging to the side of the mountains at times. You wonder why they didnt just build it down in the valley? I had been climbing almost all afternoon but being an old railway line, the gradients were gentle so the fatigue crept up on me. By the time I reached my planned camp at Carter Creek I was pretty out of it so I pitched the tent, made some substandard pasta and sauce (way too al dente) and crashed out.\n\nI woke up on Sunday after a great nights sleep to find that some sort of rodent had eaten one of my cereal bars but also nibbled holes in my t-shirt and shorts which is a first for me! Smelly cycling gear inside the tent from now on I guess. I continued riding up the Pioneer Trail before heading south on National Forest roads. This was suddenly much more rugged and remote terrain. Big views with forest as far as the eye can see - sort of what I imagine Scotland would have looked like when the Caledonian forest was still around. As I rode on I came across some quite overgrown sections but I did see a couple of pickups coming the other way which gave me confidence that there was a route through to civilisation on the other side (confidence which would soon transpire to be misguided). I practiced my bear avoidance techniques - a forest ranger in Seattle had told me that singing or talking to yourself lets them hear you coming so you dont surprise them. As a result, the wildlife of Wenatchee National Forest has been treated to an out of tune rendition of the Greatest Hits of Toby Smiths Adolescence. Looking back, maybe the advice to sing to yourself is all just a big inside joke for the forest rangers.\n\nAfter a good few hours of hard up-and-down riding, I got to the point where I expected to find a long, flowing descent to my campsite and a slap up victory dinner. What I actually found was a dead end. After a brief temper tantrum I assessed the situation. I was probably a day to day and a half from civilisation but that would involve an overnight somewhere. I had fuel for the stove, food for a dinner and breakfast but almost no riding snacks, I was low on water but I had a filter and I had passed plenty of streams so I could get more. The only certain route I had out was the way I had come so I decided to backtrack as far as I could while it was light (sunset was due in about an hour) then find somewhere to camp before carrying on in the morning. The whole situation made me realise how much wilder the US is than places like the UK. I was only 90 minutes from Seattle by car but I had managed to get into a situation where if I hadnt been carrying extra food or had a tent I would have been up the proverbial creek.\n\nAfter about half an hour I was looking for somewhere to camp when I heard a pickup coming up behind me. I decided to flag it down without any hesitation as in my mind there was no point wasting time backtracking on the bike. The truck pulled up and I put on my best hapless Englishman act and the two elk hunters (whose names I have unfortunately forgotten) said they were heading home anyway and would happily give me a lift - score! I hopped in and we drove off. Straight away they were plying me with chocolate, crisps and delicious home smoked salmon whilst expressing astonishment and the fact my bike didnt have an electric motor. We chatted about their hunting, my cycling, the fact Id managed to get lost 100 miles into an 11,500 mile bike ride and "limey hunting season" until they dropped me at the Summit Inn on the Snoqualmie Pass. A very friendly pair - not the sort of people I expected them to be when the truck pulled up and I saw the camo gear and massive rifles in the cab. I checked into the hotel and went across the road for a massive burger and pint of IPA which sure beats rationed pasta and a chilly night up in the forest. Thanks elk hunters!\n	You'll find a lost Brit	usa	if-you-go-down-to-the-woods	2023-02-17 19:46:35.124	2023-02-18 08:13:14.735	2023-02-17 19:49:21.661	1	1	2019-10-08
21	Hasta luego Mxico!	I left Oaxaca feeling extremely jittery after drinking far too much coffee from the coffee maker in the AirBnb. I picked up an excellent cycle track which took me all the way through the outskirts of Oaxaca to the small town of Tule, home to what is supposedly the tree with the widest trunk in the world.\n\nAfter a quick rest while looking at this botanic marvel, I churned out a few miles along the main road to the turn off just before Mitla. By now the winds were picking up, with little dust storms being whipped up. After turning off the main road I got to enjoy a lovely snaking descent (including a probably ill advised overtake of a slow moving bus, much to the surprise of the driver). Upon arriving in San Pedro Totolapa I tried to find an ice cream shop which Google Maps promised me existed but, alas, my search proved fruitless. During my search I bumped into a French touring cyclist, Rmi, and we had a quick chat before he carried on and I popped into a restaurant for a quick pre-dinner. In the corner of the dining room was a parrot which was greeting everyone with a cheerful buenos das, buenos das!. I joked to the unusually stern lady running the restaurant that the parrot spoke better Spanish than me which managed to raise a small chuckle.\n\nAfterwards I went to try and find somewhere to spend the night. I asked at the Palacio Municipal (a sort of town hall building which are found in most Mexican towns) and was told I could pitch my tent on the kiosk/bandstand structure just outside. In yet another example of a peaceful evening in rural Mexico, I pitched my tent to the sounds of the local school brass band giving it everything they had. The following morning I returned to the parrot restaurant for some breakfast to find that the stern lady had managed to fill the entire restaurant with chilli smoke, meaning everyone was trying to order food and eat breakfast through bouts of coughing and streaming eyes which was quite amusing.\n\nThe next day was a short one to the small town of El Camaron, meaning The Shrimp. I have no idea why a small town in the hills was called The Shrimp but there were murals featuring aquatic crustaceans on almost every available wall. I had cut the day short to avoid doing a large climb in the midday heat, a decision which I appreciated the following morning as I made my way up the climb in the cooler morning air. The rest of the day consisted of a couple more ups and downs before the long straight run into Tehuantepec. Just outside town I ran into a Russian hitchhiker with a massive beard and a slightly crazed look in his eye trying to make progress in the opposite direction. It had been a long hot day on the bike so upon arriving in town I bought a lime flavoured agua fresca (basically a weak juice) with loads of ice and gulped it down, giving myself horrendous brain freeze in the process much to the amusement of the girls behind the counter. Despite the brain freeze, I promptly bought another and repeated the process before finding a hotel for the night.\n\nIn the evening I had the privilege of witnessing what I think has been my strangest Mexican custom so far. I had noticed a crowd gathering in the square so I hung around for a bit to see what was going on. A teenage boy came out of the crowd and a cardboard donkey was placed on his back. So far, reasonably normal. Then a man set fire to the donkey with a blowtorch and the boy started to run around the circle of people that had gathered around him. OK, a bit weird but nothing unusual for Mexico. A few seconds later Catherine wheels and other fireworks started going off from the donkey, only metres from the crowd. This carried on for about a minute or so to shrieks of delight (or terror, I couldnt tell) from the crowd. Miraculously, I didnt see any injuries to bystanders despite one poor womans top catching fire. They call it "The Burning Donkey" and do it every year to celebrate the anniversary of the local secondary school.\n\nWhen I was checking out of the hotel the next morning I noticed another bike propped up in the corridor and went over to say hi to the owner. Amlie, from Quebec, has ridden down from Canada and is now meandering her way around Mexico. The ride from Tehuantepec to Zanatepec crossed a region called La Ventosa meaning The Windy One. The combination of a narrow valley and the narrowest point of the isthmus between the Caribbean and Pacific means that this area often sees extremely high winds, with stories of trucks being blown over not uncommon. Rmi had passed through a day or two before and had messaged me with stories of cars swerving around due to the crosswinds and near crashes on the bike so I rode out of town with some trepidation. Luckily, it seemed that I had picked a rare calm day but the signs of the normal weather were everywhere with wind turbines as far as the eye could see and some very bent over trees. It was a pretty uneventful ride with the only notable event being my first puncture since leaving Seattle. As soon as I arrived in Zanatepec, passers by began pointing me towards the home of my host for the night, Rodrigo. He has been hosting cyclists for over ten years now so his neighbours must know where to send the slightly lost looking cycle tourists. Indeed, Rodrigo told me that his house has gained the local nickname of casa de los gringos due to the number of foreign visitors he has! As Rodrigo and I were sitting chatting in his very lush green garden, Amlie rolled up as well. Rodrigo was the perfect host, whipping up in short order the Holy Trinity for tired cyclists: a large cold drink, a shower and a large dinner.\n\nAmlie and I left Rodrigos together the following morning and after an hour or so riding along the flat valley floor, started a long climb up into the hills and towards the border with the state of Chiapas. As is normal for cycle tourists, we rode up the climb at our own pace and regrouped at the top. Amlie said that as I pulled ahead at the bottom of the climb she thought ah there he goes, cycling up the hill like an overexcited little puppy. Ill interpret that as a compliment on my climbing ability! After a late lunch there was a descent followed by another small climb so it was likely wed become separated again so we swapped contact details in case we ended up in the same place again later The combination of a hilly day combined with long breaks meant that I had to go into full time trial mode as I raced the setting sun on the way into Cintalapa. When I got there I was so knackered that all I could manage was eating a couple of packets of instant noodles in my hotel room before crashing out.\n\nThe next day was a fairly leisurely one into the city of Tuxtla consisting of a gradual uphill before the road plummeted down into town. In the morning a car suddenly pulled in in front of me and flagged me down. Initial thoughts of an imminent run in with some slightly less friendly Mexicans were very quickly quashed when the occupants turned out to be two middle aged woman who ran a restaurant about 40km down the rode and were insisting that I should stop by when I got there. Shame on me for immediately thinking the worst! Later that afternoon I spotted the restaurant and within minutes was sat at a table with a mountain of delicious barbecued goat tacos and quesadillas in front of me which they refused to take any payment for. Maybe the Foreign Office travel advice should include a warning about excessive feelings of guilt due to incredible hospitality! I finished off the descent into Tuxtla and had just arrived at the Casa de Ciclistas when Amlie also arrived, having taken a bus from a village just before Cintalapa earlier that day.\n\nThe following day I had a rest day in the fairly uninspiring city of Tuxtla, which seemed to consist mainly of modern, ugly concrete buildings instead of anything old and colonial. The rest day was needed though as the ride the next day was basically all uphill to the tourist hotspot of San Cristobal de las Casas. I left town and soon joined the toll road after a brief friendly chat with the man guarding the toll booths who could have passed as a Bond henchman with a mouthful of gold teeth, a massive shotgun and enough ammo strapped to his chest to fight a small war. One of the advantages of taking the toll road is that the gradients are normally sensible, meaning I could spin up the hill quite easily in a low gear. It was LONG though. After just over three and a half hours climbing up through the gradually cooling air, I arrived at the top to see the town of San Cristobal spread out below me. There was a short descent before I arrived in the plaza and treated myself to a well earned victory beer. San Cristobal seems like a nice town with much more manageable temperatures and all the niceties that come with being a tourist town, like nice coffee shops, a wide variety of food and, surprisingly, craft beer! I have spent today wandering around town enjoying all these little luxuries with frequent stops for coffee and pastries or a mid afternoon beer in the sun.\n\nAfter about two months in Mexico, Im now only a couple of days easy riding from the border with Guatemala. Ive enjoyed my time in Mexico, mainly due to the variety the country offers, in landscapes, food and culture, amongst other things. Like the majority of cyclists who take a route south across the Americas, I had countless warnings from people in the US about how crazy I was to be cycling south of the border and that I should be on constant alert or I was sure to have all my stuff nicked. I am glad to report that this was completely contrasted by the countless acts of kindness I received from people in Mexico. Whenever I asked for help or a favour, the answer was almost always an enthusiastic claro que s (of course). From the people who hosted me in their homes like Sara & Adolfo in Guerrero Negro, Tuly in La Paz, Rodrigo in Zanatepec or Seth in Toluca (who also took me along to his cousins 40th birthday party for tacos, beer and bad salsa dancing on my part) to the daily smaller acts of kindness, I never really felt unsafe in Mexico. Sure, there are bits of the country that are best avoided and I was never sure whether to feel reassured or worried by the very obvious, constant presence of heavily armed police and soldiers, but on the other hand Im sure there are parts of say Los Angeles or even London that it would be unwise to explore on your own after dark as well. Like almost anywhere in the world, use a bit of common sense and youll most likely be just fine.\n\nAfter spending just over six weeks in the US and two months in Mexico, its going to be exciting heading through Central America where Ill be hitting a new country almost every few days - passport stamps galore, hasta luego!	From Oaxaca to within touching distance of Guatemala	mexico	hasta-luego-mexico	2023-02-19 20:55:10.436	2023-02-19 21:19:05.731	2023-02-19 21:19:05.727	1	1	2020-01-29
4	To the coast	\nAfter a night at the Snoqualmie Summit Inn, I left early in the morning and enjoyed a fast tarmac descent through the early morning mist back down to rejoin the John Wayne trail. I always think the best descents are the ones where youve got a lift to the top and have definitely not earned the joy of rolling effortlessly downhill! I continued down the John Wayne trail through to North Bend. I was flying along the trail with very little effort so it must have been one of those inclines that is deceptive in its appearance which explains why I was so tired after coming up the other way a couple of days previously despite not feeling like I was climbing. I stopped in North Bend for a spot of lunch and tried to go for the light option of a toasted Reuben sandwich. What arrived was my first example of American excess with two hand sized sandwiches and a mountain of chips. Luckily double carbing is not only tolerated, but encouraged during a cycle tour. I just about managed to finish it before hopping back on the bike and carrying on (albeit much more slowly after my monster lunch). What followed was an afternoon of pretty dull riding across the suburbs of southern Seattle. I had noticed that the published Adventure Cycling Association (ACA) Pacific Coast route passed through a town called Centralia so my plan was to endure a couple of days of boring suburban riding as I made a beeline to join up with the Pacific Coast route.\n\nAfter overnighting in Kent, I continued southwest to the town of Yelm. Nothing much to report as this was just another day of riding across the suburbs.\n\nI woke up the next day to a cold morning with frost still on the ground. I think it had got down to around -3C overnight which is much colder than I had been expecting. Maybe its because I was further inland and the temperature will become more temperate as I approach the moderating influence of the sea. It was perfectly bearable once Id wrapped up warm and, in any case, it soon warmed up as although it was cold, it was a bright and clear day. After Yelm the riding soon improved as I left the suburbs and started riding through rural Washington along quieter, winding roads.\n\nThe next morning I picked up the published ACA route towards Chehalis. The ACA has a whole series of published bike routes criss crossing the USA and when riding them you can tell theyve been well researched. Whereas Google Maps might take you down a larger road just because it has a bike lane, the ACA route will take you on smaller, quieter road which offers more interesting and scenic riding which Google might ignore because it doesnt have a shoulder and therefore isnt marked as bike friendly. It was also nice to have the route all planned out for me and not have to stop every 20 minutes or so to check the map to work out where to go next. The riding improved again as the route followed the course of the Cowlitz River through the leafy countryside with all the trees in various shades of green, orange and red as autumn progresses. When passing through Castle Rock I noticed a bike skills park and so, of course I had to have a go. Luckily there was no one there to see me because, as always, my off road skills were obviously lacking as I rolled around the track at an embarrassingly slow pace. I did set up my camera in the hope of getting a gnarly video of me riding round some banking but despite all my creative editing there is no way of hiding how slow and tame it looks so that video will never see the light of day.\n\nI left Kelso in a good mood knowing that I would hit the coast (and a new state) that day and could finally start making some significant progress south. I rode along the north bank of the Columbia River with cliffs on my right and the river on my left before getting a ferry across the river to Oregon. Riding onto a ferry with a bike always seems like a bit of a novelty to me. I spent the afternoon following US30 to the south of the river into Astoria. Whilst it was quite a big road, it had regular bike route signs and a pretty generous shoulder (almost the width of anther entire traffic lane) the whole way so it felt pretty comfortable. There were a series of short climbs on the way into Astoria but none of them were particularly steep so I span up them without too much trouble. Arriving into Astoria was a nice change as it seemed much more interesting than the towns I had been riding through for the past few days. I stopped off at one of the historic piers on the way into town and saw some sea lions (or big seals, not sure) before checking into my 1950s themed motel. I had read that Astoria had a reputation for being home to several good breweries and it was Friday night so it seemed rude not to go out and treat myself to a few beers. They went down very well as I watched the sun set over the Columbia River and Astorias famous bridge.\n\nThis morning I decided, that as I had been riding for seven days straight, to take a rest day to explore Astoria a bit more. Tonight Ill ride the short 6 or 7 miles to Fort Stevens State Park and camp there overnight before heading off down the coast towards some warmer weather in California. Im looking forward to the Oregon coast scenery which is supposed to be fantastic as well as bumping into a few other cycle tourists in the hiker-biker campsites which dot the coast at regular intervals.\n	\N	usa	to-the-coast	2023-02-18 08:23:55.616	2023-02-18 08:31:12.677	2023-02-18 08:29:59.244	1	1	2019-10-12
33	From Volcanoes to Desert	I left Manizales through the fumes of the stop start morning rush hour traffic. Navigating out of town was pretty easy though so I was soon on a smaller road heading to the Nevado del Ruiz national park. There was a bit of frustrating traffic here as well as for some reason the road to the national park had a massive metal recycling plant and industrial park on it! I was soon through this section though and the scenery became quite reminiscent of parts of Scotland with pine trees and a little stream running along the bottom of a grassy valley. Shortly afterwards the tarmac changed to dirt as the road wound its way up through the forest.\n\nAfter a few kilometres a Colombian cyclist who had passed me earlier flagged me down and asked where I was headed. When I told him I was headed up to the national park he warned me that he didnt think there would be a way through as there had been a large landslide the previous week. He showed me some photos on his phone and it did look pretty bad but I elected to just carry out and see what happened. If I couldnt get past then I would just camp for the night and then roll back to Manizales the following day and find another route, not the end of the world!\n\nFrom here the road conditions got steadily worse with prolonged rocky sections and other sections where there was basically a river flowing down the road which had me pushing the bike a fair bit. During a quick drinks break a passing pickup pulled over to check how I was doing and to assure me that the road surface got better in a few corners time which was music to my ears as I was getting a bit fed up by that point! I took the opportunity to get a second opinion about the landslide and asked him whether he thought I would get through. He told me that it was still a bit tricky for cars but I would have no issues getting through on a bike or on foot because the fancy hotel around there had already cleared a lot of it away to make sure their guests could get through. \n\nI was planning to spend the night at a campsite at about 3,300m with a set of natural hot springs. The last 5km were tough as I tired and began to feel the effects of the altitude. I rounded the final corner to see the sign for the campsite and a group of cyclists already there on the phone to the owner to come and open the gate. The other cyclists were a French family (Damien, Fanny, Manon, Lucie and Hlose) also on a long cycle tour. You can see their blog (with great photos!) here: https://leslamasfutes.com/\n\nAn evening relaxing in the hot springs chatting with other cyclists was just the ticket after the short but tough climb up from Manizales. Soon after dark it got pretty chilly so I was in the tent sharpish and out like a light.\n\nThe next day the plan was to finish off the climb to the national park and roll along at just over 4,000m before descending down to the town of Murillo. Id gathered some valuable route intelligence from Damien and Fanny the night before (theyd come from the opposite direction) and they said that the landslide was basically gone and the road conditions improved from here on. They did warn of lots of roadworks on the descent down to Murillo though. I set off up the climb which was indeed much smoother going than the previous day, with the tarmac even starting again! After a few kilometres continuing up through the forest I popped up into a very picturesque U shaped valley which sort of hung above the slope Id just climbed up. From here it was only a few kilometres to the start of the national park and 4,000m in altitude. \n\nId had my fingers crossed for some clear weather as the views up here are meant to be incredible on a good day. Unfortunately it was a bit cloudy in the morning and it only got cloudier as the day went on until I was basically cycling in fog. After a couple of hours I sort of gave up trying to get photos and just decided to push on towards Murillo as I was starting to feel a bit rubbish with the altitude. It was slow going with the altitude and being held at a few sets of roadworks for about ten minutes at a time. After some quite spooky cycling through the fog I was at the top of the descent down to Murillo. Basically being in the clouds and at 4,000m this was a double jacket and fleecy gloves job. The descent was actually pretty good fun with lots of sweeping curves, especially once I dropped out of the cloud and got some views. \n\nA final couple of sets of frustrating roadworks and I was in the little town of Murillo. First job - find somewhere to stay. This proved more difficult than it should have been. There were plenty of hotels but they all seemed to have their doors shut. Knocking on the doors and ringing doorbells didnt give me any joy either. A couple of them had phone numbers up so I sent a couple of text messages and then basically proceeded to do laps of the town checking each of the hotels in turn again until one of them finally replied to my text and said someone would be there to open up in five minutes. One very welcome warm shower and micro-nap later I was back out pounding the streets trying to find somewhere to eat dinner. Low and behold, every single restaurant seemed to be closed as well! I really dont know what was going on because the town was busy enough. Frustrated and hungry I went to a little supermarket and bought some stuff to make pasta and sauce in the hotel kitchen. Unfortunately I bought tomato ketchup instead of tomato pasta sauce by mistake so had a very sweet dinner - doh!\n\nThe next day I was due to lose over 2,000m in altitude so I was looking forward to a nice easy freewheel down to the valley floor. Unfortunately what I got was more fog, roadworks and lots of mud. The fog first thing was thick enough that I was having doubts about whether I should be cycling in it. It took me twice as long as Id expected to get to the town of Libano due to all of the roadworks Id got caught up in. To really put the icing on the cake, there had been a stretch of horrible grey gritty mud which had absolutely caked both me and the bike in the stuff. I managed to get the worst of it off by borrowing a bucket and sponge at a car wash in Libano. By this point it was only 1130 but I was already so fed up that I considered calling it a day in Libano (spotting a proper coffee shop and craft beer place on the main square had nothing to do with these temptations at all). I decided to crack on and had a little climb out of Libano. When I got to the top I downed a couple of cold sugary drinks and suddenly felt a lot better about life. The rest of the descent down to the valley floor was actually a lot of fun and mercifully roadworks free! There was one final blast along the valley floor with a tailwind before arriving in Lrida where I found a hotel with a hosepipe to give the bike a proper clean.\n\nFrom Lrida I had a string of pretty flat but very very hot days along the valley floor to make some progress south towards the point where I will climb back up into the hills again to cross the border into Ecuador. The first day I only managed to make it about 40km down the road to the town of Alvarado. Despite leaving at about 7.30 in the morning, by the time I got to Alvarado I wasnt feeling great in the heat (bit nauseous etc) and was in to minds about whether to continue to Espinal, which is where I had been aiming for. I decided to sit in the shade for an hour and have a couple of cold drinks and see how I felt afterwards. Felt pretty much the same after that and by this point it was midday and only getting hotter so I decided to call it in Alvarado. There were slim pickings for lodgings but I did manage to find a room with AC so I checked in early, drank a load of water and had a siesta basically all afternoon and felt a lot better by the evening.\n\nWhen I set off early the next morning it had evidently just stopped raining so it was mercifully a bit cooler in the morning. After about an hour or so on the road the rain started again which wasnt entirely unwelcome as it kept the temperature down. The scenery down here is very tropical with the coffee and chocolate plants of the hills replaced with rice fields. In fact, it reminds me a lot of cycling through Thailand with the rice fields and palm trees. As I approached Ibague I was mentally preparing to have to navigate a lot of big, busy roads. What I got instead was an incredible leafy 15 mile cycle track which was all downhill! I had to do the last 15km back on the road again but the traffic was light and there was a good shoulder so nothing too stressful. Yesterdays hotel had been a bit grotty so I treated myself to something a bit nicer this time before heading out for a late lunch. I found a pizzeria run by a father and his two sons who were all really friendly and had lots of questions about the bike and the trip. Later that evening I decided to go back there for dinner as well as they said they did pasta as well as pizza. One spag bol later (which I think they knocked up from scratch just for me) I was one happy cyclist. I forgot to take their photo so youll have to do with a photo stolen from their google reviews page!\n\nThe next two days were more of the same really - blasting along the flat main road until the heat gets too much around midday. I got a bit of luck on the ride to Natagaima when the police had closed the whole road for a cycle event. I saw a few groups of 4-5 cyclists but nothing to warrant closing the road so not sure exactly what the event was. I had a whole main road to myself basically all day though so I wasnt complaining!\n\nIm currently in the town of Villavieja where Ive taken a day off to have a little explore of the Tatacoa desert (some good photos below). Apparently this area used to be part of the Amazon millions of years ago so its full of fossils, some of which I had a look at in the little palaeontology museum on the square. From here Ill be taking some back roads towards San Agustin and hopefully gaining a bit of altitude because it is hot hot hot down here on the valley floor!	It's bloody hot down here	colombia	volcanoes-to-desert	2023-03-29 00:54:55.643	2023-03-29 00:55:16.205	2023-03-29 00:55:16.198	1	1	2023-03-28
6	Oregon Coast: Part Two	After a couple of stormy days in Newport, Martin and I decided to catch a couple of buses south to Florence to make up some ground to compensate for the days stuck due to the weather. I popped into the bike shop in Florence to have a spoke fixed when I saw two people decked out in outdoor gear walk in - prime candidates for being fellow cycle tourists. Then I heard some very familiar British accents and went over to introduce myself. Kurt and Jody, from Brighton, are cycling the Pacific coast down to L.A. It was nice to meet some fellow Brits out here and we swapped contact details to keep in touch as we make our way south.\n\nFrom Florence, Martin decided to take another bus even further south whilst I decided to gamble on what I thought was a break in the weather on the forecast and ride south just a few miles out of town and camp at the nearest state park in an effort to try and save some money. Unfortunately my gamble did not pay off. The rain started spitting down and the sky darkened ominously as I rode out of town towards the state park. By the time Id got there, registered and found a camp spot, the rain was starting to come down quite hard. I threw up the tent as fast as I could and crawled inside. What followed was one of the non-social media friendly moments of any cycle tour as I sat in a damp tent, in my damp clothes and looked at my food supplies to see what I could make for dinner that wouldnt involve going outside to use the stove in the rain. I settled on a two course feast. For main course: tortilla wraps with bad supermarket cheese and hot sauce. For dessert: tortilla wraps again but this time with peanut butter and mashed up bananas.\n\nIn the morning I realised I had misplaced my towel the previous night and went off in search of a park ranger to see if it had been put in the lost and found box. I stumbled across all the park rangers enjoying a communal buffet breakfast in one of the large huts and poked my head round the door. In a typical act of American kindness, I was told that we would look for my towel in a few minutes, but for now, why dont you help yourself to some of those fresh waffles and coffee and have a seat with us? Those state park rangers sure do know the magic words to cheer up a damp and slightly downbeat cycle tourist on a drizzly October morning. The day improved from there with the rain dying off and I managed to make it to Coos Bay despite a blustery headwind. I had checked into a motel and was just heading out to grab some food when I saw two bikes fully laden with panniers emerge out of the darkness. It was Kurt and Jody from a couple of days earlier, who by chance had booked into the same motel as me! They caught up with me in the Safeway supermarket for a gourmet deli counter dinner over tales of past cycle tours.\n\nThe next few days were spent making my way down the southern Oregon Coast camping at state parks as the weather steadily improved. There were still blustery winds but I was staying mainly dry. At Humbug Mountain state park I met Alex, who has been on the road for about five months riding a counterclockwise loop of the US starting from Houston. Weve been bumping into each other during the day and camping together for three or four nights now. Its been good having someone to chat to in the evenings and share a few beers with. I've definitely been preferring the southern Oregon coast to the north. The roads are less busy and you can actually see the coast whereas in the north the road tended to be tucked back from the sea a bit.\n\nI went to bed in Harris Beach state park feeling pretty good after an enjoyable few days riding and looking forward to hitting California early the next morning. Unfortunately my sweet dreams were soon interrupted by the sound of something big walking around the campsite. Shortly afterwards some aggressive snorting gave away its identity as some sort of wild pig. The snorting got closer and closer and became intermingled with some wild screeches. At this point I quietly grabbed my knife from my beg and held it close with one hand whilst with the other I googled things like are wild pigs dangerous and wild pig attack. Unfortunately the search results revealed that these wild pigs can be massive and I came to the sinking realisation that my little knife would probably not be much good. The next morning I woke up to find that my bike had been knocked over and the pig had managed to get into my sealed food bag and eat an apple, my trail mix and all my breakfast oats. I can only assume the screeches I had heard the previous night were screeches of pleasure as the hog devoured my banana and maple syrup flavoured oatmeal in a fit of ecstasy.\nDespite this traumatising start to the day - the sky was a perfect clear blue, I was walking around in t-shirt and shorts and I actually felt the need to apply suncream. A far cry from the previous few drizzly days. I rolled out of camp and within half an hour hit the Welcome to California sign. I stopped for the obligatory roadside photo and carried on down the road with the sun on my face, wind on my back and the Beach Boys stuck in my head. The Sunshine State was certainly living up to its name.	From damp tent dinners to California sunshine by way of wild pig attacks	usa	oregon-coast-part-two	2023-02-18 08:48:48.681	2023-02-18 08:48:50.691	2023-02-18 08:48:50.686	1	1	2019-10-23
7	Northern California	A longer post this time. Lots to cover!\n\nOne of the highlights of northern California was always going to be the redwood forests. Living for up to 1,500 years and reaching heights of over 100m these coastal redwoods are found in a belt about 25 miles wide down a large chunk of northern California. Before commercial logging began in the 1820s, there were over two million acres of redwood forest. This has since been reduced to about 270,000 acres of original old growth forest.\n\nLuckily my planned route wound its way through a fair chunk of the remaining forests. The first day in California included a climb up through a forest with a scattering of redwoods here and there. The descent down the other side was one of the best Ive had in a long long time. Fast, smooth tarmac, warm sun and views down onto the Pacific far below; it was one of those sections of road that make the days riding through drizzly headwinds all worth it. Later in the day I met up with Alex again and we entered a redwood forest proper, following a small road downhill through the forest to our campsite for the night. The forest was surprisingly spooky - dark and chilly under the dense canopy despite the blazing sun above and eerily quiet with none of the sounds you normally associate with a forest (birds, leaves in the breeze etc). To complete the image, a thick fog descended over the campsite shortly after dark - perfect stalking conditions for Bigfoot according to Alex!\n\nAfter a day following a tiny coastal road with views down onto countless hidden beaches nestled amongst the rocks, we hit the redwoods proper with the grandly named Avenue of the Giants. The trees here made the ones Id seen a couple of days before look like complete tiddlers in comparison with many of them having widths significantly larger than the span of my arms. The day finished at Burlington Campground which, with the tent sites tucked in right among the massive trees, is one of the more impressive sites Ive stayed at.\n\nOver the next few days I began to climb back up the coastal range before descending to the ocean once more and the rolling terrain of the coast road. While stopping for a cooling ice cream in Fort Bragg, I bumped into Bryan and Anna, a couple from just outside Edinburgh. Bryan is a wheelchair user and so makes his way up all the steep climbs around here using his hand cycle while Anna tows his wheelchair along with all the usual touring gear! Big kudos to them, much hardier cyclists than Ill ever be. I reached Van Damme state park that night and treated myself to what is now becoming a Friday night tradition: dinner and a couple of bottles of craft beer with a scenic coastal sunset.\n\nWhen Im touring I normally end up completely disconnecting from the news as the minutiae of Brexit or world events seem trivial in comparison for my seemingly never ending search for my next calorie hit or tasty cooling beverage. So I had no idea there were wildfires in northern California until I got a couple of messages from friends and family back home the next morning asking me to watch out for them. I had a quick look online and it seemed like they were well inland and not encroaching on my coastal route so I continued south. I made it to my planned stop of Salt Point state park with no problems and set up camp with another cyclist, Greg. Greg spent his Saturday night drinking beer and getting high while I played the role of the boring camper and went to bed early because I could feel a cold coming on.\n\nLate in the evening I thought I could hear tannoy announcements and sirens in the distance but thought nothing of it at the time. At around midnight my tent was lit up by car headlights and a park ranger walked over and told us that the area was under a mandatory evacuation and we would need to leave the state park campsite. Unfortunately he didnt have any information on where we should go which wasnt particularly helpful. The edge of the evacuation zone was a good 7 or 8 miles away and we understandably werent particularly keen on riding that far on a pitch black, winding country road. The ranger suggested that there were some dirt tracks that led down to the coast only a mile down the road and if we followed one of those down to the sea and slept there we would be safe. So off we went into the darkness (but only after Greg had downed one more can of beer and lit up another small joint). We found an open area next to the sea with multiple routes out, threw down the sleeping bags and had a not particularly restful night.\n\nThe next morning, with no park rangers present and no mobile reception, the only information I had was that Highway 1 is probably fine from an old man at the side of the road. Based on this, I decided to continue south cautiously until I could get more information. I reasoned that if I was being an idiot and riding into a danger zone, someone would turn me around sharpish. I was tired from my cold and having almost no sleep so I aimed for the town of Bodega Bay, about 28 miles away. The ride there was uneventful apart from seeing a large plume of smoke reaching out over the Pacific on the horizon. Unfortunately this cloud got closer and closer and on the approach to Bodega Bay it was clear I was riding into it. I got more concerned when I started noticing that every street had a length of police tape tied to the street sign and it became obvious these were to mark streets that had been evacuated. When I got into Bodega Bay proper it was clear the town was in full evacuation mode so I decided to get some information from a legitimate source pronto. I went to speak to a couple in a camper van to ask what theyd heard. Unfortunately it wasnt much more than me. Fortunately they gave me more food than I could carry and topped up my water bottles. They went on their way whilst I stood at the road having a think about what to do. A minute later they came back round the corner and said theyd found a police car just down the road and had asked him to wait a minute or two so I could ride over and see what he suggested I do. Big thumbs up to that camper van couple!\n\nThe police officer pulled up the latest fire maps on his computer and said that my route on Highway 1 would be completely safe. It would be pretty smokey for a few miles but even that would clear up after an hour or so of riding. With this concrete info from a trusted source, I decided to push on south and get out of the smokey area. The next hour or so was was spent riding through a very eery landscape as the smoke turned the sunlight a browny yellow colour, ash floated in the air, my eyes streamed and I covered my mouth with my scarf to try and keep some of it out of my lungs. Around the town of Valley Ford I began to see patches of blue sky again (just as the police officer predicted) and by Tomales it was completely clear. In a stroke of luck, I bumped into Alex in the shop in Tomales as he had gotten a lift through the smokey section with some friends (sensible). We rode on and managed to get a campsite in Point Reyes despite not being able to get any cash or pay on card as the power was out in the whole county so ATMs and card terminals were down. Our route followed the San Andreas fault and Alex joked that now Id experienced a wildfire, I just needed a little earthquake to complete my true California experience!\n\nWe were now less than 30 miles from San Francisco and big city comforts. As we rode in the landscape became more and more built up but everything was strangely quiet as there was still no power. I heard that something like 75% of the counties in California have no power and will probably not have it until Thursday. Apparently they have to shut off the power to entire counties when the winds get up because it can blow down power lines and spark the wildfires. Part of me thinks that the richest state in the richest country in the world must be able to come up with a better solution than to just cut off electricity to millions of people for up to a week at a time.\n\nThe Golden Gate bridge definitely sneaks up on you, one minute we were riding along a relatively benign road then I rounded a corner and there it was reaching across the bay to San Francisco (and electricity!). After a couple of rounds of photos, Alex and I rode across the bridge itself, dodging the erratic pedestrians sharing the walkway with us. The views across to the city were slightly obscured by some whisps of smoke but the bridge itself was casting a striking shadow onto the bay beneath us. After coming off the bridge at the other end we went our separate ways - me to my hostel and Alex to a friends apartment.\n\nI now have three days or so to rest and enjoy some city life comforts after 11 or 12 days riding and camping on the trot before continuing down into southern California. Ive enjoyed northern California, watching the transition from the lush green temperate rainforests to the redwoods and finally to the dry dusty grasslands that give the state its Golden State nickname has been interesting. Highway 1 has been great so far, for the most part it has been the small, twisting, sunny road by the sea but comes to mind when you think Californian road trip. Ive also been hearing a lot more Spanish being spoken as I head south. Trying to eavesdrop on some of the conversations has been a good way to dip my toe in the water before hitting Mexico!	Sun, smoke and sequoias	usa	northern-california	2023-02-18 08:55:34.3	2023-02-18 09:08:05.87	2023-02-18 09:08:05.863	1	1	2019-10-29
27	Panama & San Blas	Greetings from Colombia! I arrived in Cartagena yesterday after a five day boat ride from Panama. My arrival in South America means that this is now official an intercontinental instead of transcontinental bike ride, which combined with reaching the half way point (time flies) means this is a week of big milestones. In this post Ill skip over my time in Panama itself as there wasnt that much to write home about and focus instead on the boat trip through the San Blas islands (a group of 365 mostly uninhabited islands off the coast of Panama) which was one of the highlights of the whole trip so far.\n\nThe bus ride from David to Panama City went smoothly and was probably well advised, as I sat and watched hour after hour of boring dual carriageway through the window. Wouldnt have made for an interesting few days cycling! Upon arrival at the bus station I managed to find a taxi driver willing to put my bike on the roof of his car (didnt fancy navigating the maze of complicated junctions and dodgy neighbourhoods) and checked into my AirBnb in the Casco Viejo neighbourhood. I spent the next few days exploring the narrow streets and old buildings of Casco Viejo and treating myself to a few touristy coffees and pizzas. On my first morning there I had one of the chance encounters that seem to happen every so often on the road. Somewhere in Costa Rica Id been overtaken by two touring motorcyclists with Scotland flag stickers on their panniers. Whilst looking for breakfast in Casco Viejo, I noticed the same two motorbikes with the stickers parked up outside a cafe. I went in to say hello to the two guys (from near Oban) and we got chatting over breakfast. Turns out theyre doing almost exactly the same route as me but flying back to Vancouver (where they work) every couple of months to top up the funds before returning to their bikes in Latin America.\n\nA few days later I was picked up by the minibus to Puerto Lindo where my boat to Colombia was waiting. It would have been possible to ride to Puerto Lindo but a few cyclists have been robbed on that road in the past few months in very similar sounding incidents so I didnt fancy risking it, especially with 600 dollars in cash for the boat in my pocket! Over the next hour or so the rest of the passengers arrived and we started loading our stuff onto the boat, the Wild Card, a 25 berth sailing boat. After an introduction and briefing from our Polish captain, Yuyu (who certainly looked the part), we set sail for the San Blas islands. To get there we had to sail across some open water which was a bit bumpy, leading to some members of the group feeling slightly worse for wear. Ominously, Yuyu told us that this is nothing and these are baby waves. Shortly after dinner we arrived in the calmer waters off one of the larger islands in San Blas and anchored for the night.\n\nThe next morning Yuyu went off to the immigration office on the island to get our passports stamped whilst the rest of us had a tour around the Kuna settlement on the island. Whilst they are technically Panamanian, the Panama government has a very hands off approach to governing the Kuna meaning they run most of their own affairs. They have a matriarchal society, meaning that the women own all the property and look after the money etc. It was interesting hearing our male tour guide say things like this is my wifes house. After the tour we set sail for our next overnight stop, a much smaller island with picture perfect tropical beaches. We did some snorkelling, drank cold beers in the warm sea and played some volleyball before a barbecue on the beach and coco locos (or crazy coconuts, basically a coconut with the top cut off and rum poured in and mixed with the coconut water inside which you then drink). The crew, in true sailor style, kept coming round and topping up the coconuts with rum which meant that by the end my coconut contained a lot of rum and very little coconut water.\n\nThe tropical paradise continued for the next couple of days with more island hopping, snorkelling, enjoying the delicious food that the chef Emmanuel was rustling up in the tiny kitchen and catching the odd fish here and there. The snorkelling was great with loads of big corals, lionfish, barracuda and a huge eagle ray gliding through the water with ease (complete with a smaller fish hitching a ride on the rays back, just like in Finding Nemo).\n\nOn the evening of the third day we set off for the 40 hour crossing across the open sea to Colombia. After the rough seas on the first day everyone was slightly apprehensive about this part of the journey and there were a lot of seasickness tablets being taken. Sure enough, the waves soon grew and I suddenly felt pretty vulnerable as the boat leaned over at what seemed to me to be an extreme angle but which Yuyu assured me was completely normal. I reassured myself by reading a copy of Small Boat Safety which I found below decks and which contained some lovely engineering free body diagrams showing the various forces acting on the boat and demonstrating that it was almost impossible for it to flip over. Turns out engineering can even cure thalassophobia! It was really impressive watching the crew move around the boat with ease as the rest of us were clinging onto the nearest available surface for dear life. I didnt sleep particularly well that night as my bunk was near the bow of the boat where the up/down movement is exaggerated, meaning I was constantly being lifted off my mattress and then slammed back down into it. I also had a top bunk so I was worried that I would be flipped out of my bed and onto the poor person in the bunk underneath! Luckily the seasickness tablets were working their magic and I didnt really feel nauseous at all, just uncomfortable from all the being thrown around the boat.\n\nThe entirety of the next day was also spent on the open sea. Whilst the waves were still big, at least we could be above decks during the day and enjoy some fresh air. It was also pretty cool looking around the horizon and seeing nothing but sea as far as the eye could see. At one point Yuyu remarked on what a lovely day it was and seconds later a huge wave came through the open door of the wheelhouse, soaking us all from head to toe! His comments must have angered the Kraken or something. Shortly afterwards I was flung off the sofa and flew into the hob in the kitchen, stubbing a toe pretty hard. Its swollen up pretty good now and hurts a bit so Im just hoping its just bruised and not broken!\n\nThe second night on the open sea was calmer than the first and I actually managed to get some sleep which was a pleasant surprise. I woke and looked out of my tiny porthole to see dry land and other boats zipping about. I had a look on the map and was surprised to find we were already just off the coast of Cartagena, waiting for permission to enter the port area. Shortly after breakfast the radio crackled into life as we were given our clearance to dock. There were a couple more hours of waiting as the various immigration formalities were completed before we were all shuttled to shore via a little speedboat. Being on dry land again felt very strange as we all wobbled about, not used to not being at a constant 30 degree lean like we had on the boat!\n\nFor me, the boat journey was definitely worth the slight extra cost over taking a flight to Colombia. The days in the tropical San Blas islands were a great way to relax at the half way point of the trip and whilst I wouldnt call the open sea crossing comfortable, it was definitely a proper adventure!	Tropical paradise	central america	panama-san-blas	2023-02-21 09:11:44.431	2023-02-21 09:25:43.096	2023-02-21 09:25:43.09	1	1	2020-03-11
8	San Francisco	Ive just got time to write a quick blog post about my few days in San Francisco before leaving to continue the ride south in a few hours time. I havent been taking enough photos to do this city justice so pictures are a bit thin on the ground this time around.\n\nAfter riding off the Golden Gate bridge, I zig zagged my way across the city towards my hostel in the centre. For a city with so many cyclists buzzing about, it seems to be a bit of a minefield for bikes. There are plenty of cycle lanes and so on so Im not complaining about lack of infrastructure. There are however loads of tram tracks (bike wheel plus tram track equals a swift and unplanned close encounter of the asphalt kind) and steep ramp like hills. Im not normally that fussed about hills but every stop sign and traffic light I came across seemed to be situated on a steep section so there was a lot of huffing and puffing as I heaved my loaded touring bike away from a standing start over and over again.\n\nAfter having my first shower in two or three days (its amazing how much dirt and grime comes off after just a couple of days cycling), I headed to Chinatown in search of dinner. The Chinatown in any city is normally a good bet for fast, tasty and cheap food with the added bonus of normally being interesting places to walk around with all the hustle and bustle. Unfortunately when I got to the Chinatown in San Francisco it was almost dead. I guess it was a Monday night but Id thought that wouldnt have been a hugely important factor in a big city. I managed to find somewhere which looked semi decent for dinner (the Spice King restaurant) and got a seat at the bar and ordered some mapo tofu which was very tasty but so spicy I actually lost my voice a little bit. A Danish guy my age had come in at the same time as me and was sat just along the bar from me. Hes a software engineer working for Uber and is over here for a work trip. He ordered what he thought was going to be some normal chicken but instead got a massive platter of chilli laced chicken giblets and feet. Poor guy!\n\nThe next day I ticked off a few chores in the morning like doing laundry and heading to REI to buy more fuel for my camping stove along with a few other bits and pieces before heading to the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art. It had plenty of the usual examples of modern art (my favourite was just an A4 sized rectangle of red paint) but there were a few interesting exhibits. The first was an exhibition of photos that, technically or traditionally speaking, are bad photos because they contain flaws like bad focus, motion blur or badly placed shadows but in this case the photographer has actually made these flaws the focus of the photo. There was also an exhibition following the depiction of space travel throughout the decades from the optimistic magazine articles from the 1940s claiming wed be living on Mars by 2000 through Stanley Kubrick right up to the recent film adaptation of The Martian. The final exhibition I saw was a 45 minute long film shot using a thermal imaging camera showing the struggles of the migrants making the journey to Europe to escape the fighting in Syria and Iraq. The juxtaposition of shots of overloaded inflatable boats struggling to make it onto shore in southern Europe with scenes of comparative normality as the children ran around the refugee camps playing like children everywhere do, seemingly oblivious to their situation was interesting. That night I went to a Pakistani restaurant, Pakwan, which had been recommended by one of Alexs friends, Erin. I ordered a chicken biryani (delish) which came in an absolutely massive portion which was easily enough for dinner and lunch the next day.\n\nOn Wednesday I headed over to Fishermans Wharf for a look around. It was spectacularly tacky but still fun to have an explore. I continued the touristy vibe by getting the cable car back over the hill to my hostel. They have standing platforms where you can basically hang off the side of the cable car which makes for quite an exciting ride as you weave your way through San Francisco traffic. \n\nThat evening I had a walk around the Mission district which is the main hispanic neighbourhood in San Francisco. It felt exciting to be walking around somewhere which felt so Latin American - a reminder of things to come! I grabbed an aptly named Super Burrito at El Farito, another recommendation from Erin, which was great. A far cry from what passes as Mexican food in the UK.\n\nThursday was a slightly more chilled out day as I finished off some boring admin stuff in the morning before heading to Golden Gate park to sit in the sun and read my book. In the evening Id been invited round to Erins flat for dinner and a few beers with Erin and Alex. Alex had rustled up some delicious veggie gnocchi and baklava for dessert. It was nice being in a home for an evening rather than spending all my time in a tent, motel or hostel.\n\nIve enjoyed my few days in San Francisco and can definitely see why its such a popular place to live. It definitely has a lot more character than Seattle, the only other big city Ive visited so far on this trip and I felt more at home here than I did there. I cant quite put my finger on why this might be but you can draw some parallels between SF and Bristol (character, liberal/alternative identity and plenty of places for great food and drink). Its just a shame that Bristol doesnt have the same climate!\nToday I continue south towards Big Sur where Ive been assured by several people that I can expect coastal scenery to rival and even surpass what Ive seen so far. After that its Santa Barbara and wine country before hitting the urban megasprawl of Los Angeles.\n	Three days spent mostly eating	usa	san-francisco	2023-02-18 08:57:34.372	2023-02-18 09:33:04.222	2023-02-18 09:33:04.216	1	1	2019-11-01
