got a message from Kurt with a photo of a gargantuan portion of fish and chips and the caption only $12. I needed little more persuasion to hop in a taxi and meet them at a restaurant on the pier. The portions were indeed gargantuan, to the point where I couldnt finish it, which is very rare for a cycle tourist!\n\nThe following day I climbed out of Monterey before hitting Big Sur which, I had been assured by multiple people, would be a highlight of my ride down the States. They were not wrong, what a road! The road was hilly enough to be interesting but not so much so that I ever felt that knackered. It seemed like there was a picture postcard view around every one of the many twists and turns on the coast. I was glad that I had decided to split Big Sur into two shorter days riding as slow progress was made due to many photo stops. This stretch of road has a bit of a reputation for bad traffic among cyclists as a) it is a big tourist attraction and b) its a narrow road without many passing opportunities so drivers will try and squeeze past where they probably shouldnt. Luckily, I didnt experience too many problems. There were a couple of stretches of roadworks with traffic lights which grouped the cars up into mini convoys so I would have 5 or 6 minutes with no traffic at all then 30 seconds as they all overtook me, at which time I normally just pulled over where I could and let them all past. Later in the day I hit the 2,000km point of the trip, which after a day of fantastic views, happened beside a scrubby dried up field so no picturesque background for the obligatory photo unfortunately! The fantastic views continued the next day as I climbed above a cloud inversion layer just before the sun burnt it off. More importantly, I also had the best pastry of the trip so far: a reassuringly expensive banana and chocolate strudel.\n\nAt the campsite that night we encountered some incredibly brazen raccoons. They walked straight up to our campfire and, despite three of 