11	Central California	The farmers market in San Luis Obispo did not disappoint for dinner choices. After fifteen minutes walking up and down the market struck with crippling food indecision, I settled on a nice wood fired pizza. Once Id scoffed that, some inexplicable force drew me towards the cake stall where I spotted some pumpkin pie. Having never had it before, Ive been meaning to try pumpkin pie ever since I arrived in the US, with it being peak pumpkin season and all. However, I was determined that my first pumpkin pie experience be the real deal and not some poor chain coffee shop interpretation. I was not disappointed! I also bought two cookies that I told myself I would save for riding snacks the following day. They did not survive the walk back to the hotel.\n\nThe next few days consisted of some pretty uninspiring riding along the shoulder of the highway in the heat, but then again I guess most things would seem like a bit of a comedown after Big Sur. There were some highlights though - the day into Lompoc finished with a nice curving climb and descent into the town. Located right on the beach underneath a row of palm trees, the campsite at Refugio State Beach was one of the best of the trip so far. I arrived early enough for a quick paddle in the sea (previous intentions to go for a swim did not survive first contact of the cold water with my ankles) before a northbound cyclist, Mark, arrived. Mark used to be an art auctioneer/appraiser/valuer for Sothebys in New York before he quit a few months ago. We attempted to make a campfire with discarded palm fronds but quickly discovered that they burn very quickly and produce a lot of smoke.\n\nIn Santa Barbara I had a burrito so dense and weighty that Im sure that spacetime warped around it. I managed to roll a mile or two down the beach before I was forced to pull over and have a quick snooze in an attempt to sleep it off. I also met a Swiss couple (Dominik and Linda) who have been cycling all over the shop 