yed my time in the US and think it has been a good way to ease into the trip. However, after seven weeks Im definitely ready for something different culturally and the challenge of a different language now. Mxico, ya voy!\n	\N	usa	socal	2023-02-18 10:04:09.483	2023-02-18 10:04:11.24	2023-02-18 10:04:11.235	1	1	2019-11-19
13	First days in Latin America	On the morning of my planned departure from San Diego, I lay in bed looking at various weather forecasts, trying to decide whether to take the weather gamble and make a dash for the border or stay in San Diego another day to wait out a band of heavy rain that was blowing through. Whilst I wasnt too bothered about the possibility of getting wet, some forecasts were predicting the possibility of a few thunderstorms and I didnt fancy the prospect of biking through that if they did materialise. On the other hand, I was a bit bored of sitting around in San Diego spending money on expensive coffees to pass the time and I had been looking forward to crossing into Mexico for a while. In the end I decided to ride to the border, getting an early start to give me a nice time buffer allowing the flexibility to take shelter and wait out any thunderstorms that bubbled up. In the end, other than a thorough drenching in the first half hour of the ride, the worst I encountered was some on and off drizzle and short light showers. I soon left the outskirts of San Diego behind and it was nice to be riding on winding country roads again after so many days sharing a busy highway with lots of traffic through southern California. I climbed up through Coyote Canyon passing landscapes that looked like theyd come straight out of an old Western. Eventually I crested the top of the hill and saw the town of Tecate laid out across a hill in the distance - my first glimpse of Mexico! I rolled down the hill and exchanged my remaining dollars for pesos before crossing the border which was a very smooth experience. So smooth in fact, that I entered Mexico without realising it and had to be waved down by a man who appeared from a little office to complete the various formalities. I imagine quite the contrast to the other option of crossing at the big San Diego/Tijuana border! I checked into a hotel just in time to avoid another downpour and headed out in the evening to get my first taste of the real deal tacos. Better tasting and a third of the price of the same thing on the other side of the border!\n\nI woke to find the weather had improved significantly - they sky was still a bit grey but the forecast was for nothing more ominous than a bit of drizzle. I climbed out of Tecate and then followed rolling roads through big vineyards (this is Mexicos wine country) before arriving at an empty Guadalupe RV park. Despite appearing empty, the power was on and there was hot water for a shower which was a pleasant surprise! As an added bonus, no one appeared to take payment for my stay (Ive read that they dont tend to charge cyclists anyway). I rode through more vineyards and olive plantations before a fast descent to the town of Ensenada where the traffic got noticeably worse. If this was a taste of the riding on Mex 1 from the Tijuana border crossing then Im glad I chose to cross at Tecate and ride Mex 3! I made it through Ensenada and spent most of the afternoon climbing a winding road through the hills. Unfortunately I was sharing the road with some truck traffic and a lot of traffic related to the Baja 1000 off road motor race which was on that weekend. Luckily the sightlines were reasonably good so whenever I saw or heard something big coming up the hill behind me I just pulled over at the next available opportunity until they passed. I arrived in the dusty town of Ojos Negros before heading out to the only restaurant in town for a dinner of machaca con huevos (basically shredded beef with scrambled eggs, chilli and onion). That evening was when I first became aware of how useful being able to speak a bit of Spanish is. No one in the hotel, restaurant or shop spoke English and everything was so much quicker and easier than in the past when I would have to go through the painful and embarrassing charade of trying to communicate through miming and pointing at things.\n\nI left Ojos Negros the next day hoping to get to the top of the last climb before the descent to the coast, a distance of just over 100km. It was a windy day with the wind changing direction seemingly at random but it was in my face or to my side for most of the day. Towards the end of the day I rolled through the town of Lzaro Crdenas with about 20km to go to my planned finish for the day. However a couple of kilometres out of town I found myself crawling into a block headwind with convoys of impatient and inconsiderate Baja 1000 traffic blasting past me - not much fun. I decided to call it quits and head back to Lzaro Crdenas and try again the next day. I got almost the last hotel room in town and slept the deep sleep of a knackered cycle tourist.\n\nStopping early had left me with just under 130km (a long day for me even on a road bike) to knock out to the coastal town of San Felipe where I planned to take a rest day. Luckily the profile consisted of about 20km of gradual climbing before a 1,100m descent to the coast followed by a fast, flat tailwind assisted run along the coast. I left shortly after sunrise and had a long and windy (but enjoyable) day to San Felipe. The traffic had calmed down a lot and the road had a very lonely feel to it as I rode through boulder field strewn canyons and across cactus covered plateaus with before passing through a military checkpoint and turning south for the final run into San Felipe. I found a reasonably priced hotel where the guy at reception asked if I was Spanish or had ever lived in Spain as he was surprised at how good my Spanish was for a tourist - a nice surprise! The other surprise was when I walked into the hotel courtyard to find a massive mural of the ten commandments and a bunch of Jesus Christ has the power to change your life type leaflets in my room. Fortunately no-one has tried to convert me yet and the room has my own holy trinity of flushing toilet, hot shower and passably functional WiFi. On the flip side, I appear to have been sent a plague of mosquitos to punish me for my sins (maybe I shouldnt have ridden my bike for six hours on the Sabbath?).\n\nUp next on the plan is four, maybe five days to the next biggish town of Guerrero Negro where I might take a rest day depending on how I feel.	\N	mexico	first-days-in-latin-america	2023-02-18 10:33:06.78	2023-02-18 10:33:08.782	2023-02-18 10:33:08.778	1	1	2019-11-25
