wn figure around these parts. I spent the evening chatting with Danny and Coco (who is quite the character) before being put up for the night in a spare bed.\n\nUnfortunately the next day the wind hadnt abated at all and so I spent another six hours grinding away into a headwind but this time with the addition of some rain. Hooray! I caught up with an Australian family also riding south and rode with them for about half an hour before pushing on as I was aiming to get a bit further down the road than them that day. The road kept teasing me by changing direction slightly, raising my hopes that I might get out of the headwind for a while, but the wind seemed to magically change direction to match the road at exactly the same time. I arrived in the small town of El Rosarito just was dusk was arriving and completely worn out. In my very tired state I made the mistake of taking the first hotel room I found without asking to have a look at it first. I opened the door to find that the room obviously hadnt been properly cleaned in a long time and it was already occupied by a bunch of flies. For a brief moment I contemplated just accepting it as I was so tired but then realised that was silly and went out to try and find the owner and get another room. I was offered a different room which was a bit cleaner and only had the one fly so I cut my losses and took it. The accommodation debacle continued overnight as some pretty heavy rain blew through and the limitations of provincial Mexican hotel construction were revealed as the ceiling started leaking. Luckily it was mainly constrained to the bathroom but even still, I dont think its unreasonable to expect a hotel room to keep out a bit of inclement weather.\n\nI finally got a bit of good weather luck as the rain and wind abated just in time for me to set off the next morning. I cycled through a very soggy El Rosarito, noting to my satisfaction that there werent any other hotels in town. I would have been particularly annoyed 