vious day. I was also feeling a bit downbeat thanks to enduring several days of pretty tedious riding and suddenly feeling a bit overwhelmed by the scale of how far I still have to go. In the US, I could use arriving at each new state or famous landmark as mid term goals to break the trip down into manageable chunks. In Mexico, I havent had anything like that yet so my mind wanders to where I need to get to months down the road. I decided that riding on in this state wouldnt do me any favours so took an impromptu day to chill out and see how I felt in the morning. After a day drinking lots and lots of water and making plans to have a mini festive break in Guadalajara over Christmas to give me something to look forward to in the mid-term, I felt a lot better all round.\n\nThe ride the next day took me to the coast and the town of Santa Rosala and was a vast improvement over the past few days. Everything was so much more green and lush and there were a few nice climbs before a plummet down to the coast. The outskirts of Santa Rosala were a bit naff with a big copper mine and the ubiquitous Latin American smouldering rubbish dump but the centre was much nicer. It was the first Mexican town Id been in which had a plaza and nice church and actually felt like it had some character with groups of school children dancing in the square and old men playing guitars on street corners. I went to have a look at the church, which has a claim to fame in being designed by Gustave Eiffel (yes, the Eiffel Tower guy), and found some sort of ceremony in full swing with priests dressed to the nines and incense thick in the air.\n\nIn the morning I went out to get some bread for breakfast but noticed that loads of houses had kitchens with hatches that opened out onto the street and the housewives were cooking up breakfast for passers by. I ditched the sweet bread based breakfast idea for a quick plate of eggs, ham, tortillas and the ever present frijoles. I was offered some sort of maize 