17	Climbing Inland	Soon after leaving Acaponeta, the terrain changed from flat coastal roads to larger climbs as the road moved inland. The flora changed from grasses to flowering shrubs and eventually pine trees as I climbed. I had hoped that the increase in altitude would bring a drop in temperature but this turned out not to be the case as I rode uphill in the heat towards Tepic. Just before I crested the climb, I saw an old man in a nice checked blazer walking along the side of the road. When spotting me he switched from respectable old man to crazed cycling fan with lots of fist pumping and shouts of venga venga burro burro!. Venga means come on and burro is donkey. This can be translated in two ways. The first is an encouraging come on donkey with the donkey bit meaning strong/persistent. The other possibility is hurry up you oaf/moron. I decided to go with the first translation and gave a little sprint in response to the man's encouragement which he seemed to like. My super fit cyclist image was shattered when I had to almost immediately take a breather around the next corner and the old man came walked round the corner to see me sitting on the kerb having a drink and munching on some biscuits.\n\nI had a day off in the shadow of Tepics volcano and worked my way through the various offerings at the indoor market's food hall. Im constantly amazed by the sheer number of variations on a tortilla wrapped around a filling that the Mexicans have been able to come up with. For example:\n\nTaco - the classic and simple tortilla with meat based filling\nTaco dorado - the above but deep fried\nTostada - a tortilla deep fried while still flat and then served with toppings piled on top\nVampiro - the above but with the addition of cheese\nBurrito - similar to a taco but the tortilla is wrapped the whole way round the filling to make a tube shape rather than being open topped\nGordita - a slightly thicker taco, cut open and stuffed with fillings. Think pitta bread.\nSopes