n site which didnt make an already faffy border crossing any easier. The Nicaraguan side was particularly bad with so many bits of paper needing to be taken to so many different desks that Im still not 100% sure I entered the country legally. Still, when a soldier checked my passport 5km later he seemed happy so I must have got most of it right.\n\nAfter staying overnight in the border town of Somotillo, I set off really early in an attempt to beat the worst of the heat and winds. This turned out to be an excellent decision as the first few hours in Nicaragua were such a contrast to El Salvador and Honduras as I spun along the road in comfortable temperatures without battling into a headwind. The traffic was much lighter and I even had some improved scenery with some volcanoes on the horizon. I also noticed that I was riding through almost savannah like vegetation rather than the tropical greenery I had come to expect in Central America. Another advantage to starting earlier is that it allowed me to get a longer day in but still finish in the early afternoon. I arrived into Leon early enough to order a late lunch and watch the waiters surprise as I managed to make large iced drinks disappear almost as quickly as he could bring them out. I had a day off in Leon wandering around the town and heading up onto the roof of the cathedral for some views over the city.\n\nThe following couple of days to Rivas via the outskirts of Managua were unfortunately back to business as usual with heat, traffic and strong winds. Heading south from Managua these turned into incredibly gusty crosswinds, leaving me battling to control the bike with a three foot drainage ditch on one side and traffic on the other which is obviously a less than ideal situation. The worst is when a bus or lorry overtakes you and you get buffeted around in the slipstream. I arrived in Rivas and made a beeline for the Bomberos where they were kind enough to let me kip in what looked like a sort of classroom on