d in a while (but still probably only Premier Inn standard!) which was a nice surprise. It also meant I could rest well before the next days ride which was going to be a big one with a long 2,100m climb up to Loja.\n\nWith such a big climb on the cards I made sure I got an early start. There was some light drizzle as I started the climb which wasnt unwelcome as it kept everything nice and cool. To start with the road followed a river which made for some nice easy gradients. At one point I saw a chicken get hit by a car a couple of hundred metres in front of me. A rooster came out and started pecking around the chicken, almost as if it were trying to wake it up. How sad but touching I thought. The rooster then started vigorously attempting to mate with the dead chicken which is not quite the touching narrative I wanted for this blog post! After a couple of hours I arrived in the village of El Tambo where, having made good time so far and being roughly halfway up the climb, I stopped for a second breakfast and a couple of coffees. The second half of the climb was much tougher than the first as the road become noticeably steeper and the cloud rolled in so there werent even nice views to distract me. Just as I was really starting to tire, the gradient eased off for the final few kilometres which was very welcome. I reached the top after four and a half hours of pedalling uphill and proceeded to smash my way through several peanut butter tortilla wraps and a bottle of Coke as the clouds cleared to reveal Loja a few hundred metres below. Whilst I was making my way through my tortillas, a Colombian family pulled into the layby in their camper van. I could see them making coffee so I thought I would do my best to look cold and miserable to see if they would take pity and offer me a cup. To my surprise it worked! The coffee was delicious as well, grown by them on their farm in Colombia.\n\nAfter that it was an easy twenty minute descent into Loja where I checked into the Air