ay and b) so I would stand a fighting chance of getting some of my clothes dry. After a couple of hours lying in a hammock waiting for a break in the rain, I realised it wasnt going to stop any time soon and so decided to just make a break for it. In any case, all my cycling clothes were still soaking wet from the previous day so I didnt really have anything to gain from waiting for a break in the weather. Twenty minutes later I was dripping all over the floor of a hotel reception in Mocoa and handing over some very soggy bank notes to pay for my room. Five minutes after that I was in a hot shower with my sodden clothes hanging up all over the room with the fan blasting air at them.\n\nI woke early the next day to get a good start on the Trampoln de la Muerte. This is a rugged mountain road winding through the hills with a reputation for accidents amongst drivers and some tough climbs amongst cyclists. There were a few spots of rain as I rode through town and after the downpours of the previous couple of days I feared the worst but luckily it cleared up quite quickly. After a few kilometres on the flat, I turned onto the base of the climb and found Eneko, one of the other cyclists who had been staying at the casa, at the side of the road fixing a broken chain. I stopped to see if he needed any help and then we headed up the climb together. Initially the weather was clear but we soon climbed up into the clouds, enveloping us in fog and drizzle. This dashed any chances of sweeping vistas but it did mean that everything felt very spooky and atmospheric. After reading accounts of other cyclists riding this route I had been expecting a very tough day but to be honest, although it was a long climb, it never felt that taxing. I think partly because the inclines were never that steep and I think the surface at been regraded recently so it wasnt that bumpy. It is possible (if you enjoy suffering) to ride from Mocoa across the mountains to the next town all in one day. This d