were still many touristy restaurants that I wanted to sample! I started off with breakfast at a bakery run by a French couple where I had three delicious pastries. I think the waiter expected there to be three people eating as he brought each pastry out on a separate plate and looked a bit surprised to find just me sitting at the table! For lunch Jenny (the hostel owner) had recommended a Korean restaurant where at weekends they do slow cooked ribs. I turned up to find that Id ordered the last portion of the ribs - what a bit of luck as they were incredible. In the evening Jenny said she was heading to some sort of sunset party in the countryside and asked if I wanted to come along as well. I wasnt really for a late night spent at a party where I didnt know anyone but Jenny said she was only going for an hour or so to say hi to her friends so I thought why not. It was about a fifteen minute drive out to this old abandoned house where the daughter of an American bitcoin multimillionaire was hosting this party with professional DJ and fully stocked bar - basically like something out of a Netflix documentary! On the drive back Jenny pointed out a bunch of massive houses in the countryside which have been built by wealthy foreigners, all contained within their own compound with their own shops, cinema and hotel for friends and family who come to visit. Some of the houses have deliberately been built so you can only reach them by helicopter! I was left thinking why you would go to all the effort of moving your life abroad if youre just going to completely seal yourself off like that?\n\nThe terrain between Vilcabamba and the border with Peru is very rugged with lots of steep climbs on quite poor surfaces, with other cyclists having described it in terms like one final kick in the nuts from Ecuador and Ecuadorian road planners must be complete sadists. As a result, I wasnt going to make it to the next reasonably sized town of Palanda without a herculean effort. Luckily, there was a well placed wild camping spot about halfway which had come highly recommended by other cyclists so I set off from Vilcabamba aiming for the camp spot. The elevation profile for the day was basically a sawtooth, with four 300-400m climbs with corresponding descents in between. The first two climbs were actually quite nice with very little traffic and some big mountain scenery making an appearance. I dropped down into the village of Yangana around 11 in the morning and had a doze in the shade in the park whilst I waited for one of the two restaurants to open their shutters so I could have some lunch. Hunger sated, I did a little tour of the handful of tiny shops to try and pick up the bits and pieces I would need for the nights camping. Unfortunately I managed to time this to coincide with when the local school kicked out and all the kids were trying to buy sweets which meant I had to contend with an unruly mob of school children with zero queuing etiquette! The next two climbs were noticeably harder than those in the morning, probably something to do with the fact I was now loaded up with 4kg of water for the camp, so when I arrived at the camp spot around 3 I was pretty wiped out. The campsite was excellent, it basically consisted of a little plateau which stuck out into the valley so there were 270 degree views. All perfectly hidden from the road by plenty of thick forest which provided some good shelter from the wind as well. I managed to time dinner to perfection as the minute Id finished cooking and eating, a thunderstorm which had been bubbling up for the past hour decided to start dumping rain on me so I retreated to the tent to read a couple of chapters of my book before heading to bed.\n\nI woke the next morning to find the rain had passed but there was now thick fog. The fog was so thick in fact that when Id got up in the night to go to the loo, I almost couldnt find my tent again in the mist and dark! I had quite a lazy start to the morning as I