o the new (still partially under construction!) Hotel Calem. Zumba was a strange little town. There was no discernible centre and not much at all seemed to be open. I did see one place with a sign outside promising pizza and beer which I thought would be an excellent way to mark my last night in Ecuador. Unfortunately upon entering the restaurant it transpired they had neither beer nor pizza. Oh. Fried chicken and rice it is then!\n\nA good ride the next morning, which although hard going with more steep climbs, offered some really nice vistas across the green rolling hills. At one point I could see all the way into Peru and the town where I would be spending the night later that day. I passed through several army checkpoints on the road but was waved through all of them. Peru and Ecuador were at war as recently as 1995 with the border dispute only being settled formally in 1999. The descent down to the border at La Balsa was very steep and dusty meaning it was a proper white knuckle affair. The border was incredibly quiet, to the point where I had to wake up the Ecuadorian immigration guy to get him to give me my exit stamp! I changed some dollar notes into Peruvian Soles before spending the last of my loose change in dollars on a cold Coke and riding over the no mans land bridge into Peru. Everything was just as quiet on the Peruvian side where I got stamped in without any issues after a few of the usual questions about what Id be doing in the country and having to clarify that I was not Irish (I think a lot of the time people here see United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland on the front of the passport and latch onto Ireland as the only word they recognise, the Spanish name being Irlanda).\n\nThe road on the Peruvian side of the border was like night and day compared to the Ecuadorian side, with sensible gradients and a nice smooth surface to ride on. I think I read somewhere that Peru and Ecuador agreed to build good roads to this border crossing in