nversation with him in Spanish! When we arrived in the centre of San Ignacio he deposited me at his favourite restaurant (I needed lunch) before we went our separate ways. After lunch I decided to splash out on a slightly fancier hotel for the night. I always feel a bit guilty doing this which is silly really because a) it was still very cheap by UK standards at 20, b) good hotels are hard to come by here so I should take them when I can and c) I very much doubt Ill finish this trip and think that was great but damn I wish Id spent 10 less on that hotel in San Ignacio, will probably be the exact opposite actually! There sometimes seems to be almost a sort of competition or element of pride amongst cycle tourists to try and do everything as cheaply as possible but so long as youre not being frivolous with the money I see nothing wrong with spending a bit more to be comfortable when you can.\n\nFrom San Ignacio Ill be following a little loop out to the east through the towns mentioned at the end of the last blog post. After 8 or 9 days this will leave me in the next city, Cajamarca, where Ill plan out the next leg of my route through Peru. On the way to Cajamarca Ill have my first taste of the proper Andean climbs to come further south in Peru - time to put my big boy cycling pants on!	Across another border	peru	bienvenidos-a-peru	2023-05-28 02:00:42.282	2023-05-28 02:00:46.368	2023-05-28 02:00:46.364	1	1	2023-05-27
38	Into Ecuador	From Cabrera the first item on the agenda was riding past the city of Pasto on a couple of bypass roads. This started with a morning of climbing past some pretty uninspiring scenery, the usual outskirts of a city light industry type stuff. However, still better than riding into and out of said city with all the associated traffic! The road topped out at just over 3,200m and the second half of the right was a monster descent on a dual carriageway through a deep valley with no sharp corners so you could really fly down it. The presence of those speed traps which flash up how fast youre going only added to the temptation to go into a full aerodynamic tuck crouched down next to the handlebars. As I descended I could see the old Inca road traversing along valley wall above me. This road used to run all the way from Cusco in southern Peru to Pasto in Colombia - an impressive feat back then! The little roadside town of Pedregal made for a convenient place to break the ride to the border. Dinner was cooked on the roof of the hotel with good views up the steep valley walls towering above.\n\nThe next day Eneko and I had the option of riding all the way to the border in one go or splitting it into two shorter days. Given the reputation this particular border crossing has for spectacular queues, we chose to split it into two to guarantee we would arrive at the border early in the day. The views really impressed on the ride from Pedregal with some proper Andean scenery and some very impressive waterfalls falling what must have been a hundred metres or so down the valley walls. After a couple of hours riding I came across the first group of Venezuelan refugees walking down the road in the opposite direction in nothing more but flip flops and pulling wheely suitcases or pushing prams down the road. Over 7 million people have left Venezuela over the past several years over fears for their safety or literally not being able to make enough money to survive due to the imploding economy. The fact that the people I saw were walking away from Ecuador suggested that they must have walked all the way across Colombia from Venezuela, been denied entry into Ecuador and were now retracing their steps back into Colombia. Of course Id seen news reports and documentaries about the situation and had been expecting that Id come across groups of refugees but seeing it for real in the flesh hit me harder than I thought it would. Their situation is so desperate and its only through complete luck that I (and everyone reading this I imagine) have had the privilege of growing up in a stable and prosperous country. One flip of the coin goes the other way and it could be us trudging down that road in the sun. One group waved me down to ask how far it was to the next town and if I had any food - they got a couple of packets of my strawberry flavour biscuits, not exactly nutritious but they definitely needed them more than I did.\n\nThe next day after an overnight stop in San Juan we were riding the final stretch towards the border town of Ipiales. There was a short climb out of San Juan, with some views that whilst not as spectacular as the previous day were still good enough to distract from the tired legs. After the climb it was a downhill run all the way to the border. The outskirts of Ipiales felt pretty Wild West so I was glad that I could zip downhill through them rather than climbing slowly uphill. Approaching the border itself I was a bit apprehensive about the monster queues I mentioned earlier but in reality, I think I only queued for about five minutes in total with the longest wait being for the immigration official on the Colombian side to find the correct entry stamp (Ive been into Colombia three times on that passport so there are a lot of Colombia stamps to look through). Shortly afterwards we arrived in the town on the Ecuadorian side of the border, Tulcan, where we stumbled across some sort of youth rollerblade racing event in the main square. This was a proper professional affair with teams all in matching lycra and so on. Christ they were fast! The rest of the day was spent doing all the usual new country admin like getting a new SIM card for the phone and stocking up on local currency.\n\nThe following day I had decided to take a day off whilst Eneko carried on down the road. After a bit of a lie in and a nice breakfast at a cafe I headed to the main attraction in Tulcan which is the main cemetery. This is no ordinary cemetery though, there are hundreds of cypress trees throughout the place which have been turned into huge topiaries of all different types. I spent a couple of hours wandering around before heading back to the hotel to do a bit of bike maintenance and route planning.\n\nI woke early the next morning for my first proper day of riding in Ecuador. It did not disappoint! I was planning to take a back road from Tulcan up through the El Angel nature reserve before dropping down to the town of El Angel itself. As I rode out of Tulcan it was pretty foggy and I was worried that my day up in the hills would be spoiled by being enveloped in cloud the whole time. However, as I began to climb it became evident that the fog was going to burn off as patches of blue sky appeared. As the fog burned off, there were some pretty cool patterns being made by the sun shining through the final whisps of cloud. After about an hour or so I left the last of the hamlets behind and basically had the whole place to myself. At the same time the scenery changed from fields and farms to a much wilder landscape where it was difficult not to make comparisons to parts of South Wales or Scotland. I rode along a nice gravel track which climbed gradually as it wound its way through the hills with all the strange vegetation you get at altitude in this part of the world. About 10km from the top of the climb I came across the first of a series of about a dozen small landslides across the path. Whilst these were all passable with a bit of pushing the bike through the mud, it made for slow progress and they were often enough that it became a bit frustrating. Luckily I got through them all after about an hour I think and from there it was plain sailing (relatively so given I was climbing off road at just under 4,000m) to the top of the pass. There were some great views into the next valley from up there but I didnt hang around long as it looked like the afternoon rain was hot on my heels. It was a pretty bumpy and rocky descent down to the town of El Angel where I briefly considered carrying on to the next town of Mira. This would have been a mainly downhill ride on tarmac but Id already been on the go for five and a half hours at this point and there were dark clouds gathering so I decided to call it a day. A great days riding through some wild terrain and with just enough adventurous terrain to keep things interesting without becoming arduous. \n\nShortly after leaving El Angel there was a seemingly never ending descent as I lost most of the height Id gained over the past few days. Always a bittersweet feeling as you zip downhill thinking about how hard you worked to gain all that altitude! The views on this descent were something else but youll have to take my word for it because I was enjoying the descent too much to stop and take any photos! The second part of the ride was a bit of a slog as I made my way up a long climb on the Panamerican - it was quite hot now as well at the much lower altitude. I really started to struggle in the last 20km or so but managed to get my head down and just grind it out. Luckily Id decided at the last minute that morning to book a hotel in Otavalo rather than looking for one on arrival so I didnt have to do laps of the town looking for somewhere to stay whilst shattered. I found my hotel, had a quick shower and walked straight over to the touristy cafe across the road where I practically inhaled a delicious tomato and mozzarella salad, large watermelon juice and helping of ice cream. Feeling human again, I had a wander around the crafts market which Otavalo is famous for. Some of the stuff there was quite nice but it does detract from the whole indigenous crafts market vibe when you notice that every stall is selling the same obviously mass produced wallets, ponchos and chess sets!\n\nLeaving Otavalo I had two options, take an old railway path in unknown condition or follow the Panamerican highway again. Given I only had a short distance lined up for the day and how bad the Panamerican had been the previous day, I opted for the railway path. The path turned out to be a good choice as it was a very chilled ride through some nice scenery with only the last few kilometres being tough going when the path sort of disappeared and I had to ride across quite a lot of muddy grass which really bogs the bike down. At the end of the railway path I met up with Eneko (who Id bumped into again in Otavalo) and we road the final stretch back on the road into the town of Cayambe where we headed to the local fire station to ask if we could spend the night there. Ive done this before in Central America and it was always a case of heres a tap, heres the toilet and you can put your tent over there but this time it was a whole different experience. A fireman showed us round a lounge area with comfy sofas and WiFi, a shower block with hot showers, a fully equipped kitchen and a dormitory with actual proper beds and mattresses! To top it all off I got to regress to seven years old and sit in a big red fire engine grinning like a maniac.\n\nThe railway path from the previous day actually started again from El Quinche which is about 15km south of Cayambe so we rode on the main road south to pick up the path again. This involved an important milestone - crossing the Equator! I watched the latitude on my GPS tick down towards zero before finally turning negative beside a nondescript drainage ditch at the side of the Panamerican highwa