lled La Rinconada. The views were pretty incredible as we rolled along at around 3,800m in the valley between two sets of snow capped peaks. We arrived at La Rinconada to find a park employee in a pick up truck waiting for us (theyd passed me earlier and asked where we were heading). They pointed out the facilities to us and said someone else would be along later that afternoon to collect $5 from us before they zipped off. We got the tents up just in time as no sooner had I set up and made myself a coffee, a bit of a storm rolled in complete with thunder and lightning which is never a fun experience in a tent. I drank my coffee in my tent as I made my way through a couple of chapters of my book (and a packet of chocolate biscuits). With the rain still coming down I decided to have an afternoon snooze until it passed.\n\nI was woken about half an hour later by Eneko outside my tent excitedly telling me that Cotopaxi had finally emerged from the clouds and was in view. I grabbed my camera and emerged from my tent to admire the view and take a few snaps. There were a few whisps of cloud blowing around the almost perfectly symmetrical cone of Cotopaxi but this just added to the atmospherics if anything. It turned out Eneko had enjoyed some company in his tent during the storm - we were sharing the campsite with a very inquisitive horse and alpaca, both of whom had apparently taken a great interest in Enekos tent. He told me he unzipped the door to find himself literally face to face with the alpaca inches away! We spent the rest of the afternoon taking pictures of Cotopaxi and our camelid friend before heading up to the little communal shelter to make some dinner. With it now being dark and at nearly 4,000m it was pretty chilly so we decided to try and light a fire in the fireplace to get a bit of warmth on the go. Unfortunately all the firewood we could find was pretty damp so all we succeeded in doing was filling our eating area with clouds of smoke. No one ever did appear to take their $5 fee for camping so a free nights accommodation for the both of us.\n\nWhen I set off the next morning it was very foggy and damp which made for a bitterly cold descent out of the national park on a fast paved road. After dropping down out of the cloud base I stopped at a roadside cafe for a quick coffee to warm up before cracking on. There was a short and fast segment on a busy section of the Panamerican highway before I turned off onto a smaller back road towards my destination for the day, Sigchos. I climbed for about 15km before starting what I think was the best descent of the trip to date. This was 25km of seemingly endless curves and switchbacks going down through a series of valleys which started off typically Andean but became more and more alpine as I descended with the smell of pine wafting through the air. Nearing the end of the descent I went through an experience which is unfortunately all too common in the Andes. I could see Sigchos across the valley from me, at the same elevation and probably only a couple of kilometres away as the crow flies. Unfortunately to get there, I would have to descend another 5km kilometres all the way to the bottom of the valley and then climb another 8km up switchbacks on the other side! \nI was maybe about a third of the way up this climb when all of a sudden there was a huge clap of thunder and the heavens opened. Being on a steep switchback climb there wasnt really anywhere to stop and take shelter so I just had to suck it up and get soaked. Within about 30 seconds I was as wet as it was possible to get so I didnt even bother getting the rain jacket out as I pushed on up towards Sigchos as hard as I could. The town always seemed to be just around the corner but I made it there after I think about 30 minutes in the pouring rain. When I arrived, the hotel Id earmarked on Google Maps was all shut up (it transpired the owner was away for the week). Not ideal when youre soaking wet and cold! I couldnt find anywhere that looked like it was serving hot food for lunch either. I sat on the concrete steps under the covered sports area in the centre of town and ate a couple of stale bread rolls from my panniers whilst a host of mangy dogs looked at me hopefully and then started barking at me when it was clear I was keeping the stale rolls for myself. Things took a turn for the better after I got up to resume my search for somewhere to stay - a man came out of the first shop I wheeled my bike past and asked if I was looking for somewhere to stay. Turns out there was a hotel above his shop (not sure how I missed the sign). Twenty minutes and $10 later Id had a scalding hot shower, was in dry clothes and was under a duvet with a big cup of hot tea. If theres one thing cycle touring gives you, it is an appreciation for the simpler things in life - like being warm, dry and not having to share your disappointing lunch with street dogs.\n\nI woke the next morning to the pleasant surprise that Eneko was staying in the same hotel as me. After Cotopaxi I assumed he would do a shorter day rather than going all the way to Sigchos so it was great to find that hed made it here as well (and also endured the soaking). Eneko was packing up to leave as I was heading out on a bleary eyed search for breakfast so we agreed to meet up again later that day. The destination for the day was the village of Quilotoa, which basically exists to serve tourists going to see the lake of the same name which sits in a spectacular volcanic bowl. It was very much a ride of two halves, with the first 20km being gently rolling before a big 20km climb up to Quilotoa. I enjoyed a leisurely couple of hours rolling along admiring the views and listening to my audiobook before the climb rudely announced itself with a brutally steep kilometre or so. After that the climbing was much easier but just felt like it went on forever, probably because as this was the first time Id done extended climbing at this altitude