uth with her hand to stop her talking. This didnt stop the mum blurting out HOLA GRINGO at me as I rode past. The daughter looked like she was going to die of embarrassment but I gave her a look to say weve all been there with embarrassing parents and we all had a chuckle. In the end the 1,800m of climbing wasnt so bad and I arrived in Atillo around 3.30 in the afternoon. I asked at a restaurant if they had rooms and they instead showed me a sort of thatched shepherds hut type thing. Basic but much more interesting than a grotty room in an outbuilding!\n\nAfter all that climbing I was to be rewarded the next day with an 80km descent all the way to the town of Macas where Ill start a week or so of riding back down in the tropics on the edge of the Amazon. The first few kilometres descending from Atillo were in cloud but after I broke through the greyness the views were very impressive with incredibly steep valley walls covered in jungle towering hundreds, if not a thousand metres, above me by the time I got to the bottom. The steep valley sides made for some pretty massive waterfalls as well. Approaching Macas I could sense that I was once again in a race against time before the afternoon storm arrived so I went into full time trial mode for the final 10km into town and once again made it in the nick of time. Once the rain had stopped I headed out for a coffee and an explore. I was just thinking I should find a cafe and send Caroline and Guillaume a message to see where they had got to when who should ride around the corner but the two of them! We had dinner together that night and then went to grab a couple of beers (where the bar to my surprise stocked one of my preferred ales from back home). The next morning I made a last minute decision to take a day off in Macas (not at all influenced by the effect of two strong IPAs on a tired and dehydrated cyclist). Macas seemed like a nice place anyway and I had a few chores I needed to do and Macas seemed like a good place