44	Cordillera Blanca	A long one this time as I havent done an update in a while!\n\nI left Caraz after a few days off feeling like I was over the worst of the cold Id managed to pick up. My plan was to ride south along the main road to Carhuaz and then climb up into the Cordillera Blanca and camp just inside the national park all set for the assault on the climb up to the 4,736m Punta Olympica (where I would cross the Cordillera Blanca mountain range) the next day. However, as I was riding along the main road I felt completely wiped out and was finding the relatively easy rolling terrain way harder than I should have done with my breathing and heart rate going all over the shop. Sensing something definitely wasnt right (I probably wasnt as over the cold as I thought) I decided to do a short day to Carhuaz and rest up for the afternoon there. I certainly wasnt in the right state to do the 1,000m climb up to the national park and do a chilly camp relatively high up. After grabbing some lunch in the plaza in Carhuaz I found myself a very comfortable hotel room and had a solid afternoon nap before heading out for a late afternoon wander around town. Whilst enjoying an ice cream in the plaza, two young Italian women came up to me, offered me a free slice of chocolate cake and said theyd just opened a pizzeria a couple of blocks away. That was dinner sorted then! \n\nI was feeling much more energetic the next morning as I started off on the climb up to the national park entrance 1,000m above Carhuaz. The climb was fairly steady up through a forest with some excellent views of the mountains of the Cordillera Blanca getting closer and closer as I climbed. There was one steep set of switchbacks as the road lifted itself up into a big U shaped valley just before the national park entrance. I got to the park entrance mid afternoon and briefly considered continuing to the base of the Punta Olympica climb another 8km further on but decided against it when I checked the altitude. I was already at 3,700m and camping further on would have put me camping at 4,000m which probably wouldnt have been very sensible after a few weeks at lower altitudes. A park ranger pointed me towards a nice flat patch of grass just over the road and I got the tent pitched and a coffee on the go. \n\nIt had been a pretty chilly evening with the combination of the altitude and being nestled in the shadows in the bottom of the valley and when I woke the next morning there was a frost outside and ice on the tent. I stayed wrapped up in my sleeping bag until the sun popped up over the surrounding mountains and hit the tent and things began to warm up. I had a slightly disastrous breakfast - first I found out that the peanut butter to squeeze into my porridge had frozen solid overnight. Then whilst dismantling my stove (which runs on petrol), I watched a droplet of petrol arc gracefully through the air into my cup of coffee which I then had to pour away. Before I started the climb up to Punta Olympica I had to do 8km along the valley floor into a bitterly cold headwind so it was with some relief that I hit the base of the endless switchbacks up to the pass. The views on this climb were something else and only got better as I climbed higher. When I was nearing the top it felt like I could reach out and touch the glaciers. I was slightly concerned about the altitude, this being the highest point on the trip so far and coming after a few weeks at lower altitudes. In the end I felt OK until about 4,500m with only the final 250m or so being a bit of a struggle but by that point I knew I was home and dry so could just push through. Above about 4,000m or so I find the key is to make the cycling as easy as possible - crawl along at an embarrassingly slow pace and take the long way round all the bends to reduce the gradient and so on. At that sort of height even a few hard pedal strokes to get over a little bump can push you into oxygen debt and reduce you to a coughing spluttering mess very quickly. \n\nWhen I reached the top at 4,736m Peruvian couple on a motorcycle decided they wanted to have a very energetic conversation with me which I breathlessly tried to maintain whilst just wanting to sit down at the side of the road for ten minutes. Conversation politely ended and obligatory photos taken I set off through what is the highest tunnel in the world. This was quite a spooky experience, with 1.3km of pitch black unlit tunnel with massive icicles hanging from the ceiling and slushy ice on the ground. By taking it very slowly I made it through unscathed and began the descent down the other side. Although absolutely freezing, I think this was one of the best descents I have ever enjoyed on a bike. The views were incredible, the road surface was perfectly smooth, there was a great mix of fast and slow corners and there was zero traffic so I could absolutely fly down. At the bottom of the descent there was the town of Chacas. I had been planning to carry on to San Luis, about 22km further on, but on the run into Chacas I was completely wiped out so just decided to call it a day there and carry on to San Luis the next day. In a bit of luck, I turned up on the one night a week that the local Italian monastery cooks wood fired pizza for the village so I enjoyed my second delicious Italian made pizza in three days. \n\nOnly having just over 20km to do, I had a very lazy morning with a nice lie in in the very comfy bed at the hotel before heading out to grab some breakfast. I had a view into the kitchen from my table and could see a guy very messily breaking down raw chickens and was just praying that he wasnt the same guy who was going to make my fried egg sandwiches. On the way back to the hotel I passed the bank and there was a huge queue of people outside all in the traditional clothing and incredible hats. Leaving Chacas the road dropped down to the valley floor before arriving at the village of Acochaca. I had been planning to eat lunch here but a policeman was diverting all the traffic onto the road the bypassed the village (but it appeared that if you were on a donkey you were allowed into the centre of the village for some reason). I therefore made my way a few kilometres up the climb out of town before having my avocado sandwiches sitting on a pile of gravel at the side of the road with views down into the valley below. I arrived in San Luis to find Eneko had also arrived earlier that day.\n\nFrom San Luis it was a couple of days to Chavin and my next day off. The first of these days involved a steep off road climb and then very slow and bumpy descent to the town of Huari. Whilst attempting to wash all the road dust and grime off in the shower, the water decided to cut out whilst I was standing there covered in soap suds. Just a little bit frustrating! The next day was more pleasant with the road being mostly paved and finishing in Chavin where I managed to find a restaurant with craft beer and pizza!\n\nEneko and I left Chavin after a day off with the aim of getting to Huallanca, about 60km down the road. Unfortunately this was not to be. Id spotted a tiny road on the map which would save us about 10km and, more importantly, 500m of climbing. When we got to the turn off there was a sign saying that there were roadworks and the road would only be open for an hour between 12 and 1 in the afternoon. Normally if you ask nicely the workers will let bikes through these roadworks so we carried on and sure enough were let through the roadworks. The road followed a nice river valley and I thought we were home and dry as I enjoyed the traffic free cycling. Unfortunately about an hour later we came across another set of construction workers telling us the road was closed - and this time they meant it. There was a huge landslide which had completely wiped out the road. Not wanting to backtrack, we asked if there was another way past. A man riding a donkey told us that there was a path on the other side of the river and was insistent that it was passable by bicycle. We cycled a few minutes back to a bridge and found the path and for for the first few hundred metres it was passable by bike. After that it turned into essentially a series of stone steps cut into the steep valley sides. What followed was a couple of hours of basically carrying my loaded bike up these steps whilst being harassed by horseflies. The greatest insult though was when someone started shouting to me from the opposite bank of the river to tell me that the way I was heading was a dead end and that I needed to carry my bike back DOWN the steps and cross the river lower down. After all this we ended up on the correct side of the river and past the landslide by early afternoon. We had a quick lunch break and carried on. It quickly became clear that we were both too knackered and probably didnt have enough daylight to make it to Huallanca that day. Fortunately, an idyllic riverside camp spot presented itself at just the right moment so we decided to call it a day there and ride to Huallanca the next day.\n\nI enjoyed a bit of a lie in the next morning as I waited for the sun to rise up over the hills and warm the tent. The first few kilometres riding were a bit tough as there were some steep ramps and the surface was loose enough that I kept loosing traction and had to push. This was hard enough after a good nights rest in the tent so it would have been a real struggle the previous day! The gradient gradually eased as the road made its way up a valley. It was all quite desolate and there didnt appear to be anyone else around until we hit a small settlement at the junction with the paved main road a couple of hours later. From here there was a fast 25km descent down to Huallanca. A pretty chilly affair coming down from just over 4000m into a headwind but great views all round.\n\nWe must have angered the roadworks gods in some way because upon leaving Huallanca we got caught up in some more road closure hassle. We were only 5km out of town when we hit the roadworks and were told that the road wouldnt open until 10am - an hour and a half later. With no alternative routes we just had to sit it out and wait. When the road did open at 10 it seemed like every single car and truck queued up was trying to get through at the same time. I saw a worrying number of near crashes in the couple of minutes it took for the backed up traffic to clear. We followed after all the traffic had gone past. There was then 15km of thoroughly unpleasant riding through a continuous road construction zone before arriving into La Union where we picked up some supplies for lunch and began the climb out of town. My mood improved over the next few kilometres as the gravel road passed through a series of tiny isolated villages. I arrived in Baos late afternoon and sorted out some accommodation for Eneko and I (Eneko arrived about an hour later - it turned out that we had taken completely different routes!)\n\nIn the continuation of the theme, the next day was another long, tough one on gravel roads. Upon leaving Baos, the road began a very steep climb up out of the valley. I managed to ride most of this grinding away in my bottom gear but had to push on some sections where there was a stream running down the road and there just wasnt enough traction on the wet gravel. The rest of the day consisted of a gradual uphill trend until the final descent down to the village of Antacallanca. The highlight of the day came during the lunch break when a group of teenage boys gathered on the road, each with a tyre. It turned out this was an annual event where they have a race from one village to the next - a distance of about 5km - where they have to roll the tyres the whole way. Was not expecting to come across that in the middle of nowhere in the Andes! I arrived in Antacallanca just before dusk and set about trying to find somewhere to stay. Antacallanca is a tiny village with no formal accommodation so I started off by asking if we could stay in the town hall. That was a no go as El Presidente was out of town and apparently was the only one with a key. Next up a women offered me space in some attic room with no electricity accessed by a sketchy ladder. She wanted 40 soles for it which is the going rate for a semi decent hotel in these parts so that was also a no go. Finally we tried the local school where the headteacher let us kip on the floor of an empty classroom. This turned out to be the best option with proper loos, running water, electricity and even wifi!\n\nAfter a chilly night in the classroom we left early before the pupils arrived and set off on the final leg of this section with the larger town of Oyon in our sights. To get there we first had to climb for about 17km on a gravel mining road up to just over 4,750m. The first part of this climb was great with easy gradients alongside a series of calm lakes which reflected the surrounding mountain scenery. The second part was tougher as we entered the mining area itself. The gradients became steeper, there was traffic to contend with and I had to stop for a breather quite often thanks to the rapidly thinning air. I have mixed feelings about riding through these mining areas in Peru. On one hand, the destruction of what is an incredible environment is obvious. On the other hand, a lot of these small roads Ive been riding wouldnt exist if it werent for the mines. I am also very aware that it is easy for us Western tourists to rock up and go on about how terrible the mining is for the landscape here but it really isnt my place to tell Peruvians what they should and shouldnt do with their natural resources. The descent down from the pass to Oyon was a long, bumpy and dusty one with the road having been completely chewed up by years of mining trucks going up and down and has a result I was pretty fed up when I arrived in town. Oyon initially appearing to be nothing more than a dusty, windswept town made of breeze 