e Brazilian cyclist giving us a big thumbs up out of the window of the cab - Im glad he managed to catch a ride in the end. After a quick coffee break at the summit, Brice and I freewheeled downhill to Andahuaylas. The approach to town was pretty noisy, busy and fumey and I was preparing myself for an evening spent in a horrible noisy town but after turning off the main road and only going a couple of blocks to the main plaza everything became quite picturesque and peaceful which was a very pleasant surprise! We even managed to get rooms in the swanky plaza hotel half price because it was the low season.\n\nThe next day started with - you guessed it - another 40km climb! I think Brice and I both just wanted to get the climb done and out of the way as we wordlessly slipped into a good rhythm and made really good progress up the climb. It probably helps that we both used to do bike racing and are pretty evenly matched in terms of pace so when it comes to sharing the effort up a climb or into a headwind it all comes very easily. We were almost at the top when a dog came sprinting at me out of nowhere. Before I could do anything about it I watched in horror as it went straight for my ankle with teeth bared. In an incredible stroke of luck its teeth only got hold of my sock, shredding it to pieces but crucially leaving my ankle with no cuts or scratches at all. As it let go of my sock I got in an incredibly satisfying kick to the face. By this point Brice had dumped his bike in the middle of the road and was hurling rocks at the dog as well! Peruvian dogs really do bring out a special kind of rage and anger in the cycle tourist. The adrenaline of the encounter got us to within 10km of the summit where in another piece of luck, a slow moving truck pulled out just in front of us. Getting cut off by a truck might sound like a bad thing, but in the Andes the heavily loaded truck crawling up the mountain pass at 15mph is like the holy grail to the cycle tourist as it is norma