h some worms appeared to have gorged upon before me. The last 20km or so were on a pretty soul destroying pancake flat, arrow straight road but by this point I had a decent tailwind so I was really flying along. Id been told that if I ignored the centre of Sicuani and headed for the outskirts, there was a very quiet peaceful hotel which sounded very appealing after the pre-dawn marching band at the last place. I arrived in time for a piping hot shower and afternoon snooze before heading into town and finding a pretty decent pizza for dinner. \n\nThe next morning I woke up having slept very well and with just over 100km on the cards but the room was so cozy and peaceful that I decided I would much rather just have a lie in! Didnt really need an impromptu day off so soon after leaving Cusco but hey ho! I walked into town for lunch, finding an above average set lunch menu place. I was then planning on heading to what looked like a semi decent cafe for an afternoon coffee but as I was walking over there an incredibly strong wind started gusting about and the sky got ominously dark so I decided it was probably wise to head back to the hotel rather than get a soaking. The walk back was very dramatic with the wind whipping up little dust devils and blowing over street stalls left, right and centre! It continued to blow a gale all afternoon but the rain which looked like it was on its way never materialised.\n\nAs just mentioned, the next day was a long one at 107km. I got going just after 8 and soon after leaving Sicuani passed through a little village with some interesting architecture that stood out from the usual stuff in Peru. The town hall was all very grand and almost wouldnt look out of place in Rome whereas the houses were all very neat and wooden and appeared almost Patagonian. The strangest bit though was the church which had suffered some mishap and half of it had collapsed, but not in a messy way. It was almost like the church had neatly been sliced in half and