on that it was almost like looking out over the sea rather than over land. About half way through the day I turned off the tarmac road onto a smaller dirt road shortcut and started up the climb of the day. I put climb in inverted commas because it was only 180m or so which compared to the climbs I was doing further north is basically a rounding error. From the top of the climb it was a really fun run down to Azangaro, still on the dirt road. Azangaro itself was an absolute dump. I got a very overpriced hotel room with an electric shower which looked dodgy enough that I decided to just have a wet wipe shower instead. I went for a walk around town in the afternoon to pick up some bits and pieces but soon got so fed up with the shouts of gringo and open mouthed stares from groups of gormless drunks that I just went back to the hotel and watched a film for the rest of the afternoon. \n\nEarly start the following morning as I just wanted to get out of Azangaro ASAP. Shortly after leaving town I came to a junction where if I turned left my day would be 20km shorter but I wasnt sure what the road surface was like. If I turned right, I would have 20km further to go but I knew it was all nice smooth tarmac. After standing at the junction for a few minutes deliberating, a motorcycle came round the corner on the left hand road so I flagged him down and asked what the road was like to my destination and was reliably informed that it was also tarmac the whole way. With this information in hand, I decided to take a gamble on the shorter route. I say gamble because the directions and distance estimates to get around here can be very much hit and miss. Luckily this guy knew what he was talking about and it was tarmac the whole way. I had a quick break in the village of Chupa before the road hit the shore of Lago Arapa and then followed the shoreline basically the whole way to my destination for the day, Huancan, which made for very nice riding for the rest of the afternoon.\n\nIn the morning I set off unsure if Id cross over into Bolivia that afternoon or stop just short of the border in the town of Tilali. It all hinged on what time I got to the border as there is a no-mans-land of 15km of rough dirt road between the two immigration offices so I needed to make sure I could make it over that to the Bolivian immigration place before they closed. Adding to this was the face that Bolivia is an hour ahead of Peru so I would lose an hour of riding time to that. The initial ride out of Huancan was a pretty uneventful affair through some flat farmland before a short climb then descent into the town of Moho where I quickly stopped to grab some snacks before carrying on. There was a brisk headwind upon leaving Moho and I was concerned that things were about to get miserable but it soon died down. Leading up to Tilali there was a nice section of riding through a series of small villages on a gently rolling road. A few of the villages had faded signs up saying things like outsiders are forbidden and so on. Left over from the early days of COVID maybe? I arrived in Tilali around 12:30 so plenty of time to deal with all the border logistics. I got my exit stamp for Peru, changed the rest of my Peruvian bank notes to Bolivian money at a better rate than I should have got, spent the rest of my small change on a can of Sprite and mountain of chocolate and then set off towards Bolivia. The road across no mans land climbs over a small hill, with the Peruvian side being nice smooth tarmac and the Bolivian side being some of the worst dirt road Ive had so far on this trip. Id also stupidly forgot to download the maps for the Bolivian side so I had to do a bit of guesswork navigation through the maze of dirt roads to find my way to the town of Puerto Acosta where the Bolivian immigration office is. When I got there I had to try and explain the constitutional setup of the UK to the border official. His computer system had England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland as the options and he was very confused as to why my passport said United Kingdom of GB and NI and why that wasnt an option on his computer. That confusion out of the way, he then wasnt sure how many days to give me in Bolivia and ended up guessing and giving me 90 when I should only get 30. Thirty days is more than enough for me but I was amused at how haphazard it all seemed. Border formalities completed I went to go and set up my Bolivian SIM card before getting a room in the only hotel in town. Cheapest of the trip so far at 3 but the bed was so hard that I did end up sleeping on the floor on my camping mattress.\nA bit of a later start the next day due to a combination of sunrise being an hour later in Bolivian and general snoozing/laziness. The first hour or so was very fast along a nice flat road before I hit a couple of small climbs. After the second climb a pretty strong headwind start and I was soon grinding along the road straight into the wind. I arrived in the town of Carabuco not really feeling like riding into that wind for another 3.5-4 hours and so sat down for lunch to ponder my options which were a) stay in Carabuco and set off again tomorrow when the wind would hopefully be lighter or b) hop on a minibus to my original destination for the day, the larger town of Achacachi. After lunch I was still undecided so I went to ask a minibus driver how much it would cost to take me and the bike to Achacachi. His answer of 2 swung the decision immediately. The scenery during the drive there was just more of the same flat farmland along a long straight road so I dont feel like I missed much. When I arrived in Achacachi I was riding down the main road looking for a place to stay when a guy stopped me and said he let cyclists sleep in the indoor balcony above the swimming pool in his hotel for cheap. Milton has been hosting cyclists like this for a while now. My plan had been to leave my bike somewhere in Achacachi and then catch a bus into the big city of La Paz for a couple of days before returning to Achacachi and then skirting around La Paz on the bike. \n\nMilton was kind enough to look after my bike for a day or two so the next day I caught a minibus to the outskirts of La Paz. From here you can take a cable car down into the centre of the city. This offers some pretty incredible views as the city of La Paz is located in a bowl and all the buildings on the outskirts sort of spill over the edge from the plains down into the city below. I enjoyed a couple of days of nice coffees, nice food and museum visiting in La Paz before catching another minibus back out to Achacachi. From here the plan is to head down to the next big city of Oruru before riding to the northern edge of the Salar de Uyuni (the worlds biggest salt pan) then riding across it. There are a lot of flat, straight potentially boring main roads between here and there though so how much of it gets done on the bike and how much gets done on a bus remains to be seen!	From the mountains to the plains	bolivia	hello-bolivia	2023-08-12 20:55:10.567	2023-08-12 20:56:10.173	2023-08-12 20:55:14.448	1	1	2023-08-12
48	Salar de Uyuni	I left Achacachi at about 10am after Milton roped me into helping him make breakfast for two guests staying in the hotel part of his business - I can now say I am an expert at making arepas! The first couple of hours were on a nice tarmac road to the town of Batallas where I turned off onto a smaller road to avoid riding through the urban chaos of El Alto. As is usual for small roads in Bolivia, the surface immediately degenerated, this time to a sort of deep chunky gravel. It wasnt too uncomfortable so long as I managed to stay on a narrow strip of harder packed dirt right at the edge of the road. I arrived in the village of Pucarani around lunchtime but strangely wasnt feeling very hungry so just sat in the square and had a couple of bread rolls and a bottle of Fanta. After Pucarani my route headed into the wilds a bit more and the scenery got quite dramatic and barren as I passed through long abandoned villages. I could see snowstorms building over the mountains to the east and I could never quite tell if they were heading towards me or not but they looked sufficiently threatening that I kept a decent pace up on the bike. I passed through the town of Laja and started the final push to Viacha, my destination for the day. Unfortunately at this point the road surface went to absolute shit. It was a sort of rock solid washerboard. At least with gravelly washerboard your wheels sort of crush through the ridges, reducing the shocks somewhat. With this solid washerboard I had the choice of going at walking pace to reduce the bumps or go at a normal pace and take an absolute battering. I was cold and hungry at this point so I let a bit of air out of my tyres and decided to grit my teeth and go for the absolute battering option. My wrists and buttocks were very relieved to arrive in Viacha after an hour of bouncing up and down over the washerboard!\n\nMercifully the next day was all lovely smooth tarmac. There was a fair bit of fog about when I left Viacha but it all burnt off quickly once the sun got going properly. About 20km in I saw a protest roadblock in the distance and prepared myself to either attempt to negotiate my way through in Spanish or be stuck for a while. Luckily when I rocked up everyone seemed to be in a very good mood and I was just waved through with a friendly buenos dias. That was basically the most interesting thing to happen all day as the rest of the day was spent pedalling along a perfectly flat, straight dual carriageway to the town of Patacamaya (one of those boring roads I mentioned in my last post). I tried my best to find something other than chicken and chips for dinner but failed miserably with Patacamaya basically being nothing but a truck/transit hub.\n\nThe next morning I went out in search of a minibus as Id decided to catch a lift to the next city of Oruro to avoid another couple of days of tedious riding along flat dual carriageways. When I left the hotel I saw a group of tourists eating breakfast outside a restaurant and they invited me to join them. The majority of them were French with one Argentinian guy (Gonzalo) as well. It turned out that him and one of the French guys (Raphael) were also going to Oruro so we agreed to take a minibus there together. We arrived in Oruro around lunchtime so went out to find something to eat. None of us had any plans for the afternoon so Gonzalo suggested we have a leisurely lunch at a barbecue place. We ordered a massive mixed grill and a couple of bottles of (surprisingly good) Bolivian wine to share and were there for about three hours. It was great to have a slightly fancy meal out for once rather than the usual 15 minute pit stop for chicken and rice! After that lunch and the subsequent ice cream all I could manage for the rest of the day was to waddle to my hotel and have an extended snooze.\n\nI took advantage of being in a proper city and took the following day off to do some chores like route planning and laundry as well as go out for a nice coffee (and finish digesting the previous days feast). It looked like there were yet more tedious roads ahead so I elected to take another minibus ride the next day to the town of Salinas de Garcia Mendoza on the northern edge of the Salar de Uyuni (the worlds largest salt pan) where the riding would get more interesting. Salinas had a very edge of the world feeling about it as a freezing wind howled through the crumbling streets blowing clouds of sand and dust about.\n\nI left Salinas with the bike heavily loaded with food and water for a couple of days on the salt pan. To get to the salt I had to ride about 30km along a sandy back road through a string of tiny half abandoned villages. I had been worried that I would need to do hours of pushing the bike through deep sand but it never actually got that bad and I managed to ride through all of it without needing to resort to pushing. Just before lunch I crested a hill and saw the blinding white expanse of salt stretching across the horizon. I descended down to the tiny village on the shore of the salt, topped up my water supplies and rode out onto the salt. The initial transition from land to salt feels so strange as your brain tries to work out what youre riding on. Some people have said that the white colour and crunching sound makes your brain think youre riding on snow. There is also this worry in the back of your mind that youre going to fall through the salt at any moment. This confusion all passed in a few minutes and I was soon effortlessly rolling along the pancake flat salt with a nice tailwind. The surface of the salt actually varies quite a lot. In some areas there are really smooth well worn jeep tracks you can follow. In other areas there are no tracks but the surface is still smooth so you can zip along whereas in other bits there are bumpy nodules of salt so you have to slow down a bit. After a while I stopped to cook up some noodles for lunch and take a few photos. Taking the sunglasses off for photos on the salt is always a bit uncomfortable because you have the intense sun in a cloudless sky above and all the light from that being reflected off the salt which is a blinding bright white. My destination for the day was one of the islands on the salt pan, Isla Pescado. It is possible to sleep on the salt itself (in fact thats what I did last time I was here in 2013) but it is basically impossible to get tent pegs in because the salt is like concrete and with high winds forecast for the late afternoon/evening I thought it sensible to try and find somewhere with a bit of shelter to sleep. With no path to follow and no reference on the horizon I had to navigate by following a straight line Id drawn on my GPS. When I got to Isla Pescado the wind was already gusting pretty strongly so I did a lap of the island to scout out a camp spot. I had hoped that one side of the island would be sheltered from the wind and I could get the tent up on one of the beaches but it seemed like no matter which side of the island I was on, there was a strong wind blowing off the vast expanse of the salt pan. After a while I spotted a little mini cave and decided that I would probably be better off just putting my sleeping bag and mattress out on the ground there than trying to get a tent up in the very strong winds and risking breaking a tent pole or something. The wind howled until about 11pm but I was pretty cozy all wrapped up in my little cave and managed to get some excellent photos of the Milky Way.\n\nThe next morning the wind was a bit calmer and I headed a hundred metres or so out onto the fresh salt to make myself breakfast as the sun came up. It was bitterly cold until the sun began to warm things up a bit meaning I had to try and make my fancy coffee with two pairs of gloves on - a new coffee snob challenge! After breakfast I got everything packed up and headed back out onto the salt. Unlike the previous day, this time I had some jeep tracks to follow which made navigation a bit easier. My first stop was at Isla Incahuasi, the main island which most of the tourist jeep tours head to. It was about 20km from Pescado to Incahuasi but the complete lack of distance perspective on the salt meant that Incahuasi looked like a faint mirage on the horizon until I was basically on it. As I approached the island, there were a bunch of tourists filming me ride in from the salt on their phones. There then followed a ten minute question and answer session with them all crowded round me, not quite able to believe that I was cycling across the salt pan. If you want the experience of being a celebrity for a few minutes, cycle onto Isla Inchuasi from the salt! I had thought about spending a second night camping on the salt pan on Incahuasi but by the time I arrived it was only 11am and I was enjoying the strong tailwind that had built up so I decided to press on to the other side of the salt pan, about 70km further on. I kept myself entertained by tweaking the playlist on my phone, seeing how long I could ride with no hands and trying to take photos that convey the weirdness of riding across this huge expanse of pristine white salt. I got to the town of Colchani on the opposite shore of the salt pan about 3pm and had a quick look around for somewhere to stay. The town was completely dead though, with its main purpose being to serve the jeep tours that pass through and once those have finished for the day, everyone goes home. I made a snap decision to carry on to the tourist hub of Uyuni which was just over 20km further on. This would mean a very long day of 120km but the by now howling tailwind meant I was in Uyuni in absolutely no time. The wind was strong enough that I was averaging 35km/h on the flat with basically no effort and at one point I decided to go into a full aerodynamic tuck and give it the beans and very briefly hit 52km/h! For reference, that is the sort of speed that top Tour de France riders will hit on the flat and I was on a fully loaded touring bike.\n\nI had a day off in Uyuni to shower off the accumulated salt and grime and enjoy a couple of excellent pizzas in a touristy restaurant. I also visited the train graveyard which is essentially a collection of rusted old trains from the days when Uyuni was a mining hub. Fully recuperated, I set off into an absolutely freezing morning to start the final few days towards the border with Argentina. The first 20km was pretty dull but after that the scenery started to improve with some badlands/desert type stuff going and lots of frozen over rivers. There was also an old railway line running parallel to the road with some cool old bridges which looked straight out of the 1930s. I had been climbing for most of the day at a barely perceptible gradient so I got to enjoy a short descent down into the little mining town of Atocha where after a couple of ice creams I decided to call it a day. \n\nThe next day was a bit tougher with at just over 100km and a decent amount of climbing. I managed to keep myself motivated by telling myself that the final 40km were all downhill so really I could kid myself that it was only a 60km ride! The first 60km consisted of a gradual rolling climb through lots of mines and a chilling blustery wind. I made good progress and was soon at the start of the downhill portion of the ride, the first part of which was pretty steep and on a nice sweeping road. This, combined with a good tailwind and the fact the road was three lanes wide with no traffic meaning I could take the racing line, meant that I hit 90km/h which I think is a record for the trip so far! I enjoyed about 10km of this white knuckle descending before I hit the valley floor and the gradient eased. The scenery down there was really cool, with more of that badlands scenery I mentioned earlier. At times it really felt like riding through the Wild West in the US rather than southern Bolivia. I arrived into Tupiza and had a little explore of the town centre. Having lost almost 1,000m over the day, I was below 3,000m for the first time in weeks. It felt strange (and great) to walk around in the evening without a puffy jacket on and for there to be greenery and birdsong rather than dust and a howling wind. To complete the Wild West theme for the day, I stumbled upon an American diner themed restaurant where I had some decent nachos for dinner. I also ordered a beer, not realising Id ordered a huge litre bottle so I wandered back to the hotel slightly more squiffy than Id anticipated!\n\nI had another long day on the cards the next morning but I had the motivation of knowing if I made good time I could cross the border into Argentina that afternoon. The terrain for the day was reasonably flat apart from a 15km climb back up to 3,500m in the middle of the day. I pushed on at a decent pace in the morning and made it to the top of the climb at about 11:30. From there it was a rolling 45km to the border town of Villazon. This border has a reputation for huge queues of 4-5 hours so Id decided that if I arrived and the queue was reasonable I would cross the border that day, if the queue was massive I would find a hotel on the Bolivian side and cross the following morning. First though I had to try and find some US dollars. The intricacies of the current messy currency situation in Argentina mean that the best way to get hold of Argentine pesos is to get hold of dollars outside of Argentine and exchange them for pesos once in the country. Doing it this way means you get the unofficial black market rate rather than using a cash machine and getting the official rate set by the government. The difference is significant, by changing dollars I would get about 1,000 pesos to the pound whereas by using a cash machine I would only get 500 pesos. Unfortunately it seemed that everyone else had had the same idea as the only cash machine which gives out dollars on the Bolivian side was empty so I had to take out a couple of days worth of Bolivian currency and change that for pesos instead. The rate wasnt quite as good as for dollars but it was still decent. Currency faff completed, I rode down to the border expecting to see a massive queue but I ended up being the only person crossing, lucky! I was across the border in about fifteen minutes with the only hiccup being the Argentinian customs guy joking that he would have to confiscate my stash of chocolate which momentarily sent me into a panic!\n\nAcross the border from Villazon is the Argentinian town of La Quiaca which is where I am right now. Its a very pleasant little place which is unusual for a border town. Ive also been surprised by just how different it is from the Bolivian side. On the previous border crossings in South America the towns on either side have had the same vibe with the only discernible difference being new money and maybe some different food. Villazon and La Quiaca are like night and day with Villazon being your typical dusty Bolivian desert town with lots of car horns and rubbish. La Quiaca feels much more European and peaceful with a few long tree lined avenues. The food is also already a massive improvement on the endless chicken and rice in Bolivia. In my day here so far I have feasted on lomo a la frontera which is basically a fat steak topped with tomato and red pepper stew and a couple of fried eggs, as well as an assortment of empanadas from various street food stalls. From here I have a week or so of lazily rolling downhill off the altiplano through a series of apparently picturesque little villages before I arrive at the finish line in Salta!	Like cycling on another planet	bolivia	salar-de-uyuni	2023-08-26 00:30:39.571	2023-08-26 01:03:02.536	2023-08-26 01:03:02.514	1	1	2023-08-25
