day. For the first hour or so there was a noticeable wind but nothing that would impede my progress too much. However, soon after the wind really picked up and changed direction to be directly in my face. The ride quickly became a bit of a slog as I just got my head down and counted down the kilometres. After a few hours mainly spent trying to get into an aerodynamic tuck on my touring bike, I was very relieved to arrive in the town of Abra Pampa. After checking into the only hotel in town, I went out to try and find a late lunch. This being siesta time in Argentina, the options were limited but I did manage to find somewhere open just round the corner from the bus station. In the latest Latin American oddity, there was some sort of ceremony to celebrate Pachamama (a sort of Andean mother nature type goddess) going on. This seemed to mainly involve filling the restaurant with smoke from a little fire on the concrete floor and getting battered from a massive dirty pint in a big clay pot. The lunch was decent however: spaghetti with a more than passable ragu type sauce. \n\nMercifully the next day the wind had switched direction by 180 degrees so I had an absolutely howling tailwind for most of the ride. There was a very gradual 25km climb out of Abra Pampa but with the tailwind pushing me along it was a piece of cake. From the top of the climb it was downhill for the rest of the day with some incredible scenery along the way. Lots of weird and wacky rock formations and impressive canyons. I stopped for the day in the town of Humahuaca, which, although more touristy than La Quiaca and Abra Pampa, was still small enough to be peaceful and retain most of its character. I had another day off in Humahuaca, mainly to go and see the Serrana de Hornocal, a mountain with an impressive set of brightly coloured stripes from the various bands of minerals which make it up. The viewpoint is about 20km out of town up a 1,500m climb on a dirt road so I headed to the bus terminal to try and find a lift. This being Latin America, this wasnt difficult. Within seconds of walking into the bustling terminal I had multiple taxi drivers and within minutes I was sat in a 4x4 pickup on my way to the Hornocal with Manuel from Venezuela and an Argentinian couple. The mountain was spectacular, with the colours almost seeming unnatural. We timed our visit well as we had the viewpoint basically to ourselves and just as we left the crowds started arriving. Once back in Humahuaca, Manuel and I had a quick walk around town before popping into a restaurant for some lunch and a couple of afternoon beers. \n\nI had a very relaxed start the next morning as I only had about 40km to do to the next town of Tilcara, all of it downhill. Before leaving, I made another attempt to get cash from a Western Union place (I still hadnt managed to get hold of cash by this point) but once again didnt have any luck. I left town about 10:30 and about half an hour into the ride stopped at a nice roadside cafe for coffee and cake - I could get used to this style of cycle touring! A very easy ride basically freewheeling downhill for a couple of hours. On the outskirts of Tilcara I spotted a restaurant with whole legs of lamb on a wood fired barbecue so I had to stop there for lunch and try my first proper Argentinian barbecue! I enjoyed a very leisurely lunch with generous helpings of roast lamb and a couple of glasses of Malbec before riding the final two kilometres to my hotel. Unfortunately I hadnt realised that they were two kilometres up a pretty steep climb, not ideal after such a decadent lunch! When I checked in to the hotel, I got a free upgrade to a duplex type room with a living room downstairs, massive bedroom upstairs and a balcony which was a nice bonus!\n\nI had a couple of days off in Tilcara in order to delay my arrival into Salta until I would be able to check into my AirBnB. The first day I did a nice little hike to La Garganta del Diablo (The Devils Throat) which is basically a cool narrow little canyon which you can scramble up until you arrive at the waterfall at the head of the valley. The second day I took a bus to the nearby town of Pumamarca. I had been unsure about whether to stay in Tilcara or Pumamarca but after visiting Pumamarca Im glad I stayed in Tilcara. Pumamarca was nice but it was tiny and the entire centre was full of handicrafts stalls all selling exactly the same thing. Good to visit for a day but I think I would have got bored very quickly if I was staying there for a few days. The main highlight of the day though was that I FINALLY managed to get some cash from a Western Union! I took out about 100 worth, which given the exchange rate and small denominations of notes here, meant I was carrying around an absolute brick of cash. \n\nThe next day was an excellent day out on the bike to get to the city of San Salvador de Jujuy. I bumped my way down the cobbled streets of Tilcara to rejoin the main road. The first 40km or so were incredibly fast with a strong tailwind and consistent downhill gradient. I think I was averaging 30km/h or so which is really zipping along on a loaded touring bike. Just after hitting the 40km mark, the wind direction changed 180 degrees in the space of a kilometre or two which was really strange, I was riding along the bottom of a big valley so maybe there was some weird wind pattern coming off the mountains either side. I only had to struggle into the headwind for 30 minutes or so until the downhill gradient steepened enough to overcome it and then I had soon dropped enough in altitude that the wind died down pretty quickly. On the approach to San Salvador I noticed that the old Ruta 9 was running basically parallel to the modern main road so I turned off and followed the smaller old road. The smaller road alternated between good gravel and quiet paved roads through a series of little villages. The altitude drop was really noticeable by now. I think Id dropped just over 1,000m over the course of the day and the scenery had changed from dry high altitude desert to something much more green and lush with lots of palm trees and blossom. The smell of grass was also really noticeable which sounds weird but when you think that Id just spent months above any sort of tree line it sort of makes sense. I think the last time Id seen grass was back in northern Peru. I really liked San Salvador, lots of old buildings and leafy boulevards. I went for an explore in the early evening and it was nice to walk around in shorts and t-shirt with no strong wind blowing dust through the streets for once. I found a bar serving decent beer at the side of the plaza and had a couple of pints of IPA and a massive roast pork sandwich. The only downside was having to fight off the incredibly brazen pigeons who kept trying to nick bits of my sandwich with absolutely no fear at all.\n\nI had (another) day off in San Salvador which I spent exploring the city centre, drinking nice coffee and reading my book on the roof terrace of the hotel. The next morning I had breakfast and packed up my bike for the final time. Loading my panniers onto the bike that morning was the first time that the prospect of finishing the ride actually felt real. I got the hotel receptionist to take the obligatory last day photo of me and the bike before I set off into the basically deserted Sunday morning streets of San Salvador. As I made my way through the streets and onto the cycle path out of town, the sky was ominously grey and cloudy and for a while I was worried that the last ride of the trip was going to be a wet one! The road out of San Salvador was reasonably busy until I hit the town of El Carmen where all the car traffic turned off onto a newer motorway and I turned onto the old road. This was an incredible road to ride, basically no wider than a cycle path and almost zero traffic. It winds up a gradual climb through a mountainous cloud forest type landscape. It is obviously a popular route for cyclists as I was overtaken by a few road cyclists out for their Sunday morning rides. Upon reaching the sign marking the top of the climb, I had a quick break to have a snack and savour the fact that after the seemingly endless climbs of the Andes, it was now at last downhill all the way! The tiny old road continued its curving route down the other side of the pass before joining a slightly bigger road near the bottom of the valley. Id always thought I would dawdle through the final few kilometres of this ride, not wanting to finish, but in reality I absolutely hammered it through the final 15km or so as I made my way through the outskirts of Salta. I was weaving my way through the streets in the centre of Salta when suddenly the big pink dome of the cathedral on the main plaza a block or so away appeared above the the surrounding buildings. One final detour due to the one way streets not being in my favour and 14,724km, 13 countries and 190,656m of climbing (and one pandemic induced hiatus) after leaving Seattle, I finally sat down for a much anticipated massive celebratory steak sandwich and a cold beer!	The grand finale	argentina	salta	2023-09-18 23:41:37.955	2023-09-18 23:41:40.9	2023-09-18 23:41:40.894	1	1	2023-09-17
